A Republican strategy to hinder Obama's reelection
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight against electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and claims that electoral fraud is less frequent in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, the American states are responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
And along the same lines a majority of American governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that made the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon has spread following the November 2010 elections, which saw the gain of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of voting rights were introduced in 41 states during 2011.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID in addition to proof of U.S. citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the election and withdraw the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
The State of Indiana was the first to require it.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
As a result, Republican authorities were quick to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 do not have an identity document with these characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
As a result, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income individuals.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000 per year, 18% of citizens over 65 years of age and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have a photo ID.
And there is more.
In many states students, the voters who vote the most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs that usually vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by these clubs.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It appears that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers in 2011 supported legislation abolishing same-day voter registration in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a service to help voters who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 led to a drop in the rate of new voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers adopted legislation in five other states that favored shortening the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 election in Florida, 33% of early voters were African-American, while African-Americans represented only 13% of the state's voters.
The same was true for Hispanics.
These represent only 11% of the electorate, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, represent no more than 46% of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible, in part, to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of 34 states adopted the law requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of voting rights in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have adopted such laws account for 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Prostate cancer screening: To test or not to test?
In fact, the PSA test sometimes produces erroneous results, with false negative or even false positive results, after which it is decided to perform useless medical interventions.
This is more than enough reason to make men, already reticent in themselves, doubt whether or not they should be screened.
To take the test or not?
We have sought advice from two specialists.
Studies in the United States found a high rate of infection among the sample groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and make firm recommendations.
On the other hand, the European study showed a certain difference in mortality between patients who had undergone screening and those who had not.
The study, with a 12-year follow-up, also showed that there is a 30-40% chance of metastasis if the screening test has not been performed.
I therefore recommend testing from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if your father has had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American origin have a higher risk rate.
The key is to make a good decision once cancer is detected.
There are aggressive cancers and other cancers that are indolent.
It is really necessary to make the patient understand the degree of risk of his cancer. He should be offered all possible options and not necessarily treat prostate cancers that are not life-threatening in the long term, in which case active surveillance of the disease should be chosen instead.
Today, many men who have been found to have cancer are not treated because the cancer is not aggressive or life-threatening.
Instead, we suggest active disease surveillance and, if the disease progresses, we offer treatment.
We increasingly determine precise criteria for deciding who should or should not be treated.
I recommend taking the test in any case.
But it is important to talk to your doctor to determine whether or not you should be tested.
Movember has created, in collaboration with the International Society of Urology, a tool to evaluate the pros and cons of PSA testing.
This document can be downloaded (currently only in English, but translations will be available soon) at the following address: http://ca.movember.com/fr/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening.
Prevent disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle recipe to prevent cancer.
Despite the progress of research, the adoption of healthy lifestyle habits remains the best way to reduce the risks of suffering from the disease.
We estimate that if everyone ate well and moved enough, 30% of cancers could be prevented.
"If no one smoked, that rate would rise to at least 50%," stresses André Beaulieu, spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
Instead, we assessed that about 10% of cancers are hereditary.
Many others remain totally unexplained.
For the Canadian Cancer Society, the fight against smoking remains a priority despite the decline in the number of smokers.
Tobacco is linked to 85% of lung cancer cases.
It is also a risk factor for other types of cancers.
It greatly harms people's health.
"Today, there are still 1.5 million smokers in Quebec," said spokesman André Beaulieu.
An encouraging fact: 10 years after quitting smoking, the risk of dying from cancer is reduced by half.
Weight
Fatness and obesity also favor the onset of the disease, according to the SCC.
They increase the risks of breast, colon and rectal, esophageal, pancreatic and uterine cancer.
"Research shows that regular physical activity throughout life protects against breast cancer," they add.
Food and beverages
The agency also recommends limiting the consumption of red meat.
In large quantities, they increase the risk of colorectal cancer.
Deli products should also be avoided.
The preservation of meat for smoking, drying or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogenic substances.
"They can damage the body's cells and lead to the development of cancer," they explain.
