Moreover, M. Beaulieu insists on the importance of discussing one's concerns and family history with one's physician.
"Getting screened does not cause cancer."
The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
What is more, it is the particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model: our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists it is not entirely clear that it is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that a new particle exists and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Moreover, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seems to confirm that it is, although more data is still needed to be completely sure.
In any case, we assume that it is Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem small. We will see what it is.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that rule and don't try too hard, because you will end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that such a law also exists: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" consisting, roughly speaking, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And on the other are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place at the same time.
According to Berkeley Lab's The Particle Adventure website, which, by the way, is extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we will not discuss here, and "force particles", through which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson is in some way related.
These bosons, it should be emphasized here, are not the exotic critters we might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as a "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "messes up" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave is born (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is none other than a photon; that is, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
It is the same with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it requires extremely high energies, a bit like a frozen pond in which only a thick rock can slide across the surface.
This is why it takes a huge particle accelerator like the one at CERN (the large hadron collider is a ring 27 km in circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool to explain the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stay stuck to a refrigerator door by itself.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (such as the photon, by the way) do not.
But what can all this research "contribute", asks Mrs. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (SM), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and SM predictions.
For their part, many fervently wish they would meet, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that plugs certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has huge shortcomings, such as the fact that it does not propose any explanation for gravity (oops!) or for dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the Universe (another oops!).
But we have found no such differences at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of such research on our day-to-day lives are difficult to predict, but we do not think we would be wrong in saying that it will have none.
Just so you see: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers in laboratories had no inkling of the revolution their work would bring about.
They hinted at scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as the physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962, has already said, at the beginning the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Imagine...
And furthermore, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light sensor in 1969 in the course of his research in optics.
Although it was by no means his original intention, this sensor now serves as the "eye" for all the world's digital devices, earning him the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
That is not to say, of course, that the LHC activities necessarily want to transform our lives, but you never know....
Palliative care. The best way to die... | Le Devoir
In its Dying in Dignity Commission, Quebec recently debated the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate should be resumed soon while a bill is being prepared.
However, within this essential domain, there is still much to be done.
Le Devoir has tried to get a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his Montérégie apartment.
The prostate cancer that was destroying him had given him a two-year respite.
"They had given me five years to live, but I've already had seven," he says, lying on his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care center in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, we can't be prepared for this," he continues.
The disease has wreaked havoc on him: an enormous weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone and even eating on his own.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he resignedly accepts to be helped to eat.
Brave, he even smiles and talks to strangers who give him attention, bring him medicine and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is to be cured of my diarrhea, it's humiliating," she confesses.
A few hours later, the team found a remedy.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man pees standing up," relates Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois center.
Going back to their childhood, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"That depends on the person's ability to accept that regression," he notes.
Because, in the opinion of most people working in palliative care, the great moments take place at the very heart of that regression.
All patients entering the Victor-Gadbois palliative care center have cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
In that state, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide the "curative" care.
The greatest fear of Mrs. A., 89, is to die "conscious and drowned".
But the disease has made him discover his children.
"I have some good kids," he adds.
"I have no more wishes left in this life," she says, before agreeing to be fitted with a mask to help her breathe.
And he expects, in the next few days, a last visit from his son who lives in Italy.
At Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers offers body care and nutritional assistance.
They are palliative care given when nothing else can be done.
To help make your death more comfortable.
In Quebec, we have one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It is very little, since we know that we will all end up dying someday.
Here, life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the center's doctors.
Whether at the physical, emotional or spiritual comfort level.
The dying person is offered mouth rinses with brandy or Pepsi, according to demand.
Diabetics no longer have their blood sugar levels controlled.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served a beer to Mr. X, who died during the course of the evening.
This morning, his son finished his beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help both patients and their loved ones," relates Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois center, the days are never the same.
Next to a 94-year-old man savoring his last family reunion in the courtyard, well placed between his pillows while everyone drinks to his health, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife and two children, after having tried everything to survive.
"For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," worries Dr. Christiane Martel.
Some 53% of the patients admitted to the Victor-Gadboisarrivent center come from home and 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
Seventy-seven percent of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient reaches the terminal phase of life, whether at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois center and the Grand Montréal home palliative care society, specialize almost exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this major relative gap in Quebec health care that makes many palliative care doctors fear the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by eminent figures in palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec healthcare system is not competent enough to ensure that anyone has the right to quality palliative care before agreeing to proceed with euthanasia.
"Recently," he relates, "I have seen a patient spend 14 days in the ER in severe pain with no relief.
I fear that patients may wish to die just because they do not receive adequate care."
And at the same time, many oncologists stick with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognoses.
Hélène Richard's hopes of survival were already at an all-time low when she left a grueling chemotherapy treatment.
"When I told my oncologist that I wanted to stop treatment, she told me she was very sorry I wanted to stop fighting," he recounts.
"However, she had told me there was nothing else to do!"
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank their caregivers for not attending to their requests once their pain has been relieved by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful when it comes to pain management.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative home care at Grand Montréal, patients do not respond to pain treatment in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, physicians often resort to palliative sedation, which serves to put the patient to sleep until the time of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can't pretend we don't understand that part of suffering.
Increasingly, unrelieved disease will have the possibility of palliative sedation.
Sick people who are not relieved all say the same thing: "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want euthanasia", it means "I want to be relieved".
