Large-scale real estate scandals in Quebec
Road network officials, BTP businessmen, political party fundraisers and Italian mafia specialists tell, day after day, what they know about a formidable "system", of which the construction industry, civil servants, politicians, trade unionists and mafiosi are part.
An "industry" that cost Quebec taxpayers too much, especially in the 1990s and 2000s.
"It's funny how the system pulverizes once we've hunted down the big media," ironizes Jacques Duchesneau, a deputy in Quebec and former head of the Montreal police.
He led the outbreak of the scandal in 2011, which was made possible by an in-depth investigation into embezzlement linked to road contracts in Quebec, which the Liberal premier at the time, Jean Charest, had only consented to delay.
The "Duchesneau report" established a direct link between the industry, clandestine party financing and corruption among officials.
"Since the start of the investigation in 2010, the transportation ministry alone would have saved $1 billion in contracts," containing some of its instincts to keep a proportionate share.
The Charbonneau Commission "has already brought down two mayors," he adds, while hoping to be able to "demonstrate the stratagems behind the individuals".
A permanent anti-corruption unit, created in 2011
The Permanent Anti-Corruption Unit, created in 2011, is also implemented with its team of government auditors, investigators and analysts.
This unit operates in addition to the "Marteau squad" police officers, who, since 2009, have made Montreal's "sewer cartel" restrain itself when it comes to inflating contracts.
In recent weeks, the unit has proceeded with the serial filing of fraud and corruption charges against municipal officials such as Frank Zampino and Richard Marcotte, mayor of a suburban city.
Next on the list would be Gilles Vaillancourt, who has just resigned from his post as mayor of Laval, Quebec's third largest city.
He is suspected of having pocketed repeated bribes in exchange for public contracts.
Montreal road engineers and businessmen of Italian origin, such as Tony Accurso and Lino Zambito, have been formally charged.
The latter has caused a stir by explaining to the commission the mechanics of the "system" for obtaining public contracts.
He himself paid for three years 3% of the value of the contracts obtained in Montreal to a middleman linked to the mafia who transferred the money to Union Montréal, the party of Mayor Gérald Tremblay.
M. Zambito handed out money left and right during the 2000s, awarding more than 88,000 Canadian dollars (about 68,000 euros) to provincial parties, especially the ruling Liberals.
He also admitted having organized an illegal fundraising campaign for the former Liberal deputy prime minister, Nathalie Normandeau.
Inflation of the cost of sewerage contracts
In Montreal, the corruption "system" worked effectively.
Gilles Surprenant, a former public works engineer, explained it perfectly to the commission: in ten years he received gifts, invitations to trips, golf tournaments, restaurants, field hockey games and bribes from construction companies totaling $736,000, all in exchange for sewerage contracts whose costs he inflated.
Other road officials have admitted that they received money for inflating invoices by 30% to 40% as false extras.
In addition, an organizer of the mayor's party, Martin Dumont, accused M. Tremblay of having deliberately turned a blind eye to a parallel budget and filled his coffers with dirty money.
In the wake of these revelations, M. Tremblay resigned in early November and led Montreal into a huge crisis.
Chantal Rouleau was one of Montreal's first elected politicians to sound the alarm.
As mayor of the Rivière-des-Prairies district in the east of the island, she opposed since 2010 the sale of a municipal land purchased for $5 million and resold for $1.6 million to developers at the height of the real estate boom.
70% of election campaign money was dirty money
Of the investigation that will finally be carried out, she assures that she pulls "by a thread to be able to understand the functioning of the system, infiltrated by ants, to stop the gangrene and catch the culprits".
He adds that the process is "painful, but positive".
We are cleaning up the wounds but it would take a clean investigation unit in Montreal and being very vigilant so that dubious practices are not repeated.
How to do the cleaning.
Regularly.
Jacques Duchesneau, for his part, declares that "officials have stolen hundreds of millions of dollars", but he is particularly concerned about the role of "elected politicians who are aware of the scheme".
Estimating at 70% the proportion of dirty money that went into financing electoral campaigns in Quebec, he ironically says: "I've been told that this is only a pale reflection of reality".
The Quebec government proposes to limit donations to parties to $100, but that will not change the donation, according to him, "as long as election expenses are not strictly limited, there will be dirty money in politics."
He advocates a complete overhaul of the system for awarding public contracts and party financing: "we cannot sink any lower; going to the bottom of things, with courage, will allow us to rebuild the house with more solid foundations, with more controls and laws".
If this story tarnishes the international image of Quebec and Montreal, Mr. Duchesneau invites those who laugh to look in the mirror.
