With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
Quite the opposite of today's monetary exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing charges between parties.
Moreover, as is often the case with technologies, the political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, composed of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency convertible into dollars, euros, etc. and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows peer-to-peer file sharing.
Nearly 200,000 transactions have been recorded thanks to 15,000 computers on the network.
And about a thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a form of payment.
The bitcoin price, after peaking at $30 (€23) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning today to hover around $10 (quotes are listed on the bitcoincharts.com site).
This is not at all impressive when compared to global changes in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in it in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
In it, bitcoin was described as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as "credits", which are used to advance in a video game and can be earned by playing or can be purchased (and sometimes even redeemed).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with the changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are at once ledger repositories, verifiers, issuers of currency, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two e-mail addresses in the form of e-mail.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a double key encryption system.
The network can then verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin exchanges are recorded in the public ledger, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
The winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding this complementary line.
This is a file slicing phase, i.e. the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "slicing" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more leading zeros).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, in order to commit fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be orphaned, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, most likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred millionth, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed with each increase in computing power.
Network life already has its ups and downs.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in deposit have been stolen.
"The bug used does not affect the protocol itself," assures Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the potential for money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Major players such as Wikipedia reject payments of this type.
Others, such as the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, the "giant sales" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars was exchanged," rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on this currency, believes in the potential of this technology in addition to the transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are thus cheaper.
The bearer also manages his or her identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for retailers, who do not have to install new terminals or software.
All they have to do is provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to replace hierarchical systems with more horizontal systems.
"It will take a while for Bitcoin to catch on, but 2013 could see a shift," he predicts.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB expects to reassess the various risks, currently considered high, should this currency be successful.
