A Constitution with forceps in Egypt
It is a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants him full powers, he decided to play the all for all.
He caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Only a week ago, the head of state had given the Assembly two more months to finish its work.
And for almost two years Egypt has been using a provisional text, which has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to judicial imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delirium" and continues to "betray his word" and "trample on the law".
Its supporters claim that this is a measure to end the institutional and political crisis more quickly and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be organized within the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy rages throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he stated in an interview to the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "either you vote for my text or I maintain full powers", powers that will supposedly come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in this strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, overwhelmingly Islamist, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the liberals did not attend the meeting.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 substitute members were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As expected, the articles voted unanimously.
Commentators are amused, on the other hand, by the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day was expressed practically at prayer time, so much so that several committee members went so far as to think that the Constituent's clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the subject of all eyes, ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of the Sharia constitute the principal source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental demand, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the rules", which would have allowed for stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than a publicity stunt.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to Article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular for anyone who is to confirm its conformity with Shariah laws.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "the people called upon to speak out are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy."
The liberals' fears are further heightened by the fact that the next chancellor of that university would be considerably less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are in the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who worked on this text are not ulema but academics, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity surrounding Article 220, as the terms used mimic religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that could be raised in the future would be to what extent are civil judges competent to rule on all of this?"
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms referring to the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few in number compared to what they were during the previous regime.
Another point of contention: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the military's wishes, the revision of the defense budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defense council.
Nor will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as requested by associations for the defense of human rights.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticidal.
The offense of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
Moreover, none of the articles emphasize the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture under Article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was due to appear on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this noon.
Supporters of the head of state demonstrated on Saturday.
In Israel, the holy land, the navel of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land combines the majesty of biblical truths with modern comfort and pristine nature.
"AIF identified the five most important reasons why one should visit Israel.
Reverence in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this "baptismal font" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of Jesus' miracles: the turning of water into wine at the wedding, walking on water, the calming of the storm and the full nets.
In this same place, Jesus appeared before his disciples after the resurrection.
But the greatest number of holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers walk here the Way of the Cross or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "Via Dolorosa").
It begins in the Fortress of Antony, the Praetorium, where the trial took place, and continues through the streets of the Old City, goes to the Holy Sepulcher on Mount Golgotha, the place of the crucifixion, to the Stone of Anointing and to the burial place of Jesus.
In this same place is also the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
And the Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built on the site where, according to Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site for Jews, the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave notes here with their wishes, which will later come true.
Vertical travel
The ruins of the Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret refuge against enemies, which Herod the Great had built in 25 B.C. for his family.
They are located on mountain cliffs at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And to get there by their own means, can only those who are dedicated to climbing.
Others can reach this historic summit by funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort Hermon, where in the winter months there is a large influx of tourists.
Bus services are available from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly inhabited the mountaintop.
Visiting unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You will not be able to visit them all in one trip.
But it is worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting ones.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It contains the ancient Dead Sea Scrolls or Qumran Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean desert, and some 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is worth a visit.
His exhibition of paintings includes canvases by impressionists and expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the Al Basha bath museum, which are some rooms of old Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea it is worth visiting the exclusive private museum Ralli, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dali.
There are no tour guides or souvenir stores.
Admission is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, displays one of the most dramatic pages of history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars are shining.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives ring out.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health
Israel's three main tourist areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they bathe even in the winter months, as the water temperature does not drop below 21 degrees and the air heats up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and they bathe there all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is located at the lowest point of the planet: 417 m below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily sustain even those who cannot swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People come here to undergo courses of treatment with salt water, brine and healing muds and fortify their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put their broken nerves in order.
Touching the mysteries of antiquity
They are preserved in the old part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route linking Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through it.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this very place, he led a long and happy life.
Tourists love to stroll through the narrow streets named after the signs of the Zodiac.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of your "same" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find newlywed couples coming from all over Israel, and even from other countries to have their pictures taken.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the chief city of Judea and the residence of the Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists remember
If you travel to Israel, don't worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
Money for this trip is not recommended in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily exchanged into shekels (currently $1-3,8 shekels).
Urban transportation consists mainly of buses, but in Jerusalem there is a fast tramway and in Haifa there is the only subway line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Lower City with the Upper City.
Actually, it is from a subway funicular.
Traveling by any type of public transport costs 6 shekels and for this price you can travel by transfer for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturdays.
From Friday night until sunset on Saturday, markets and stores close and public transportation stops working.
But on Sunday morning a new work week begins.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes combining milk and meat.
They offer a wide selection of dishes based on beef and lamb, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a variety of sauces, falafel, which are ground chickpea balls, fruits and vegetables.
In the streets of Israeli cities, there are no stray dogs to be seen.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that "walk at will" in an imposing manner.
At night you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Purrers love crowded places and do not refuse treats.
Car rental, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day.
In addition to insurance, which costs $15 per day.
And renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels per day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in figures
More than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
Most of those arriving to tour the country and rest were citizens of the U.S., Russia, France, Germany, Italy, the U.K. and Ukraine.
The Promised Land, from January to October 2012, was visited by 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists, which is 51% higher than the same rate in 2010, before the cancellation of the visa regime on February 9, 2011.
"The great and powerful" will take you to Moscow: migrants save for language
While congressmen and human rights advocates argue about the consequences of the law on mandatory testing, scammers trading in "fake" certificates have already appeared in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
They are mostly citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed at home.
Since December 1, a law has been in force, according to which every labor immigrant will have to take an exam to test his or her knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule is applicable only for those who intend to work in the service delivery sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
Eventually, however, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, the tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will not be enough to take the language exam, but also the Russian history and the fundamentals of legislation.
Knowledge of the language must also be confirmed in order to receive and renew the work permit.
Exceptions are citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Persons who managed to obtain their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 will not be subject to this law.
Utility, fatality and defense of rights.
The network of examination centers will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian institutions of higher education.
Immigrants will be able to sit for the tests in all cities, right now in Russia more than 160 such centers are open.
The initiative on the introduction of the examination was supported by deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights advocates, long before the law went into effect, managed many times to ask this question to the press: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will compulsory language knowledge bring about, both for Russians and for immigrants themselves?
First of all, say representatives of the Immigration Service, this will reduce the number of people suffering from "labor slavery".
Many people today talk about defending the rights of labor migrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the Russian Federal Migration Service representation in Tajikistan.
The defense of your rights must be initiated prior to your departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of the cases.
The problems are the immigrants without profession, education, those who do not know the language and do not pass the medical control.
Without an understanding of the language, Sebelev says, the prospective immigrant will be doomed to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, will stick him with a "little paid trip" to a creepy, cramped shack, where he and dozens of others like him languish for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive countless complaints from our immigrants.
"In their homeland they are promised one thing, but upon arrival they are cheated, deprived of their passports, not paid the promised wages," confirms the Head of the Labor Immigration Directorate of the Tajik Immigration Service, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't get mad, little boss!
In the meantime, however, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia admit that not only do they not know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also in their own language they write with difficulty.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as their own misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families do not even have anything to feed their children, let alone clothe them, shoe them and buy them what they need for school.
As they reach adolescence, these kids venture out to work at the first opportunity.
It is difficult if you don't know the language, they admit.
"One feels humiliated and inferior."
However, as far as the language law is concerned, advocates make an important point.
The exams will be conducted only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no exam and, consequently, no official job.
Meanwhile, most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden to strangers"
Many visitors say that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in the bureaucratic obstacles and the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a fake registration can be done quickly and for only fifteen hundred rubles.
Employees of the Russian police know that we usually carry false documents, we are not registered and cases of extortion appear.
"They ask us for one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea," Tajik citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting."
On the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it became clear that not only immigrant registration documents can be forged.
Several "fake" certificates of language proficiency have already been seized by Federal Immigration Service officials.
The forged documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came into the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that "diplomas" cannot be bought, converge government officials and rights advocates.
So far, the authorities can promise immigrant workers who would not have been able to successfully pass the exam the first time more time to study the basic language course.
In addition, immigrants who do not speak Russian will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
