"For now, tricking the brain is not so easy."
The topic of augmented reality, so popular among fans of modern technologies, is lately perceived normally mainly through the prism of special glasses.
Earlier in the summer, Google demonstrated a moving model at its annual conference, and later in November it became known that Microsoft had also filed an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the 3D interactive technology group at Microsoft's Cambridge lab, Izadi Sharamom, it emerged that for the company's scientists, glasses were already a thing of the past.
They are attracted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the object of study of your research group?
- We are dedicated to human-computer interaction, but we also try to push the boundaries of this interaction.
For now humanity in its great mass has been trapped in the stage of working with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with the finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else does the future hold?
- Although Kinect has brought interaction to the physical level, much of it still occurs on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
Input has improved (the system receives more data), and output is still not very good.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design technologies.
The IT world must be liberated to our world, to the physical world, to make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the surrounding space.
Then we will be able to complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, to hell with those silly virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think they overestimate it?
- Of course, it cannot be considered a panacea, the privacy issue remains to be solved, since we do not always want others to know about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for device control in public places, we had a project where we thought about gestures, but not in single movements, but shorter ones.
In addition, gestures were captured not by the device's camera, but by a wristband that recorded bone and muscle movement.
For now it is very large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How is it?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this can of soda?
You will talk and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that's going to be very hard to recognize.
- You mean, you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at the moment?
- Not necessarily, but it is a mutual approach.
I believe that in the near future we are going to have to work mainly on designing new types of sensors that can accurately determine a person's reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they provide good depth resolution, which is very important.
- If we're talking about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what may be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be nice to get 8 megapixels at the speed of 1000 fps.
But the question is not in the megapixels, but in the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From the latter point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
In other words, we have to remember not only the resolution in the X and Y axes, but also in the Z axis.
Also important is the speed, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps is really low, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our lab in Redmond, made a contact sensor with adjustable processing delay from 1 to 100 ms and it is worth mentioning that modern mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human-machine interaction.
I would find an equivalent of such a device very useful for my work, but one that does not require contact so that the frames per second are more.
- And there is no need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is in fact the infrared emitter and the second the receiver of the reflected signal.
But the third camera is actually a simple sensor of the visible tuning fork.
It is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or, on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible Kinect analog, play with the curvature of camera placement and see how this would help determine three-dimensional position.
- As far as I recall, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not introduced its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that, from the point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all the time holding up a smartphone in your hands, is not very comfortable, but I think: the best option would be a "transmutable" augmented reality when, on the basis of a cloud platform, you could move from glasses to smartphone,
Glasses are very personal devices, therein lies their strength (private things only you will be able to see them), but also their weakness: a glasses-based augmented reality will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from the movie "Iron Man", but also to any mere mortal.
There is one problem with this idea that critics often point out: there is no tactile feedback!
The hands feel nothing!
What answers does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth may well be the addition of tactile sensations.
In the meantime, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as a support for the image.
It registers the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are truly aimed at bringing tangibility to these "images in the air". For example, the interference of several ultrasonic beams directed at a specific point where the finger is located gives a sensation similar to what one feels if someone were blowing on one's fingertips, but that sensation is still very weak.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to trick the brain?
Make him think he feels what it seems he should feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here lies another challenge that we will have to struggle with for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very confined space believe that they are going to an open, almost endless space. We are also working on the idea of treadmills (not like the ones in gyms), moving platforms, as well as that of giant balloons.
For now, fooling the brain is not so easy, it still needs to be worked on for many years.
That's what makes working with virtual reality attractive to researchers, that many things are in a state of total conception.
