Problems of reproduction in space began to be addressed with the flora.
Experiments with plants have been carried out for half a century.
Four generations of orbit-grown peas were no different from terrestrial varieties.
Then came the breeding of insects in the orbit, small fruit flies, the drosophilae.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent into space to test how the embryo develops under weightless conditions.
The result is a normal chick.
But then the problems start.
"The problem is that this chick has to find support, it has to stand on its own feet and start moving," explains Vladimir Sychev, the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Biomedical Problems (IPBM) of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
