As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without concrete data. However, Germany is still a model in some respects, but it is not possible to say exactly where it is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of inspectors?
That's for sure not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make this kind of comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model must face a great number of problems.
If this were not the case, it would not be of any benefit to them to collaborate with our office, don't you think?
With regard to our country's legislation, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean for your office, and does it have any impact?
Taking into account that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet manifested itself in the control actions.
Since we perform ex post controls, a certain time lag is necessary.
For now, it can be seen in the process of preparing future controls: we have initiated a new tool for "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have had almost 14,000 public awards passed and analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and similar.
Do you consider that the approval of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it is a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I believe that this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope it will be.
The problem that may arise is that the regulations may be "tightened" and become impossible to comply with.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programs of the regional council), and every law not respected in the matter of public awards meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
So does it make sense to tighten the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal failure, which has no impact on decision making.
Such a system will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of it?
We will see where this new path leads us.
The prime minister has recently stated that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls on the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc" system prohibited or permitted?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits something, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such controls and demand obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and allow it," but you can't say we'll do business as usual.
In the law on public procurement, the regulations are quite strict as to how to act formally. And that is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
Roads are icy, although most of them are passable
In several places in the Czech Republic, roads are icy and snow-covered.
Although most roads are passable, extreme caution should be exercised on some of them.
Karlovy Vary region
Today in the morning the roads in the Karlovy Vary region were passable, but they were icy and snow-covered.
Temperatures will drop to between five and ten degrees below zero. During the day the thermometers will rise slightly.
It has stopped snowing in the region and the snow cover is thin in the low areas.
On the other hand, on the ridges of the Montes Metálicos, snowfall reaches almost 30 centimeters.
In some places visibility was still poor due to fog, according to information from the region's road operations control center.
The R6 expressway and the first-class highway in the region are now passable without restrictions.
However, extreme caution is recommended, especially on some bridges whose surface may be icy and slippery.
Likewise, all second and third category roads, including mountain roads, are also passable.
However, in some of them there are still stretches with ice and packed snow.
Increased attention must be paid to the road, especially in higher areas.
Pardubice and Hradec Králové Region
On some roads in eastern Bohemia there is danger of frost, and in higher areas and in the mountains a layer of snow may have formed on the roads, the Road and Motorway Directorate reports on its pages.
Road operators warn drivers about the danger of ice patches forming, especially in higher areas of the Pardubice region.
Frosts may occur in the vicinity of Lanškrouna, Ústí nad Orlicí, Poličky, Svitav or Vysokého Mýta, and especially on second and third category roads.
Roads I/43 and I/34 in Svitav have been chemically treated.
There is snow especially on the roads in the mountains from Krkonoše to Orlické hory.
There is a layer of packed snow on the higher areas of the roads in the municipalities of Rychnov nad Kněžnou and Trutnov.
In the eastern Bohemia area, skies will be clear to partly cloudy today, with no precipitation.
Temperatures will generally range from three below zero to one degree positive, with a weak wind blowing.
Pilsen Region
Roads in the Pilsen region are passable today morning, although extreme caution should be exercised and it will be necessary to adapt to the weather.
In the early morning hours there will be frost, temperatures will range between three and nine degrees below zero.
After the snowfall and the subsequent drop in temperatures, some roads could also be covered with ice.
In some places drivers will encounter fog, but visibility will gradually improve.
This is according to information from the region's highway operations control center.
The D5 highway is passable almost without restrictions, although extreme caution is recommended, especially on the road between kilometers 80 and 131.
The surface of most premium roads is dry and free of ice.
In the area of the Pilsen-Tachov road bordering Germany there may be stretches with ice slabs.
Second and third category roads are wet, so, in this case, there is also a warning of icy sections.
Drivers should be more cautious, especially on less traveled roads in the Šumava area.
Olomouc Region
Drivers heading to the higher elevations of the Olomouc region will encounter partially dumped snow.
After chemical treatment, snow still remained on the Červenohorské pass and on the track in the direction of Videlský kříž.
Road operators removed the snow overnight; about three centimeters of snow accumulated on the Šumper road, according to road administrators.
In the rest of the region, most roads are passable without restrictions.
"In the higher areas of the Šumper road, snow remains.
Drivers on the Červenohorské pass will encounter half-dumped snow in the direction of Jeseník," an operator of the Šumper road administration confirmed to the ČTK today.
On the ground and at night, his colleagues also came to the Jesenická and, after chemical treatment, the slopes in the higher areas are now clear and wet.
On the Olomouc road the roads are passable without restrictions, on the Šternberská road drivers should drive with caution on forest sections, where the roads are still wet.
Ústí nad Labem region and Liberec region
Road operators in northern Bohemia have reported complications on different stretches in the early morning.
Apart from some places where it has snowed or frozen, according to the police database the mountain road between Telnice and Knínice in the Ústí nad Labem region is closed.
Temperatures remain below freezing, even in the lowest areas, so ice and snow obviously remain on the road. In contrast, in the lower areas, especially in the southeast of the central Czech massif, there are no problems and the roads are generally dry.
At the moment, no service complications have been reported.
Road operators have warned of ice in the vicinity of Štětí.
According to meteorologists, conditions have been ideal overnight. During the day rain and melting snow is expected and at night the skies will be clear and icy.
From general roads, unfavorable conditions have been announced on road I/13, on the border between the Ústí nad Labem region and Liberec.
The road between Telnice and Knínice had to be cut because of tree branches that had arched over the road under the weight of the snow.
Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to accumulate positive energy.
It is said that in a little less than a month the end of the world is coming, what do you think about it?
It's just one of many alarmist news stories we like to cling to.
The Tap Tap band likes to make jokes about this and we like to say that we are the only band in the world that manages to gather enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to avoid it.
In addition, in December you are organizing a truly original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain it to our readers?
This is a statewide benefit that we have been planning for the past two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar set for December 21 at 11:10 am.
The day before, on December 20 at 9 p.m., we will organize 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at approximately the same time as the Mayan calendar ends on the island of Kiribati in the Pacific Ocean, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
Initially it was my idea, then we were forging the project together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and avoid the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar we have also created a unique collection of items: boots, t-shirts, bags and original key rings against the end of the world that can be purchased at www.e-tap.cz, another way to support us.
The group The Tap Tap, along with other performers, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, entitled "End of the World, Cancelled".
Currently very popular on YouTube, will you be able to be heard at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and it will be just the last, well, as long as everything goes well and the world doesn't end....
It will be sung by all the performers at the same time in the three concerts.
The anthems will be linked together simultaneously thanks to a special live broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomáš Hanák has written the lyrics of this song and plays the leading role of Jesus in the video clip, where Xindl X also sings...
How did this collaboration come about?
We even work together with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, in addition to organizing many charity events and concerts...
We are committed to participate in this project.
It has been proven that most of them are interested and enjoy working with us.
What will the money raised from the concerts against the end of the world be used for?
To equipment for the barrier-free educational center Studeo, which we carried to completion in its sixth consecutive year with the civil association Tap in Jedličkův ústav.
Students at the Jedličkův ústav school are regularly visited by teachers with whom they engage in fun and interesting activities.
Students do not have sufficient financial means to pay teachers and we make an effort to make this possible.
As part of the completion of the works in Jedličkův ústav, there will be a separate building to which we will move with this project.
Each concert features several groups and performers.
What are the selection criteria?
We try to put together a program that will appeal to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform in Prague.
For more detailed information, please visit www.kpks.cz.
Do you plan any other similar "spectacular action" in the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Pražské jaro festival, so here we will certainly prepare an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and I, personally, taking advantage of the fact that we are in the United States, would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalistic, so far you have performed for example in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group formed by people with disabilities.
How are the logistics and organization of these trips?
It is not as difficult as it may seem at first glance.
There are five members in electric wheelchairs, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments....
However, we have managed well so far. ČSA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which never ceases to amaze me.
Even in Moscow, from where we recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to the trips abroad you can compare the different attitudes of society towards the disabled and other aspects.
What have you encountered so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have witnessed that, in the East, there is still a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, where it is still rare for a person to move around the city center alone in an electric wheelchair.
Something as common as, for example, giving preference to someone in a wheelchair in an elevator is not common there.
Fortunately, a civil association has been created that strives to thematize the problems of people with disabilities.
In what aspects should we follow the example of more advanced countries?
There are many aspects in which we are behind....
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the people it directly affects.
In London and Madrid it is very normal for people with a severe disability to move around on their own in public and to be able to go to the toilet, to the museum, wherever they want...
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to participate actively in social life, in this aspect, with The Tap Tap we are a little ahead of the curve!
A respectful or barrier-free society is one thing, but when the time comes when eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers emerge, everything will really start to change.
So far, these are isolated cases of people who have great willpower.
The Tap Tap group is currently very popular, but if we look back a few years, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I joined as an educator in Jedličkův ústav, where I had a lot of young people around me who wanted to pursue something.
And since I am a musician, playing, among others, the saxophone, I founded an amateur group with a co-worker.
And over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, it got a little out of hand (laughs).
However, the popularity did not come until the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that it helped us a lot to connect with famous singers and also to work actively to promote the group.
We came to the conclusion that work that is not seen is as if it did not exist.
Thanks to European Union grants, we can also afford quality teaching staff, equipment, etc.
Did you intend to go that far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I saw the potential that was there, that something can be done differently.
Show business is full of things that are similar to each other.
Logically, in its own way, everything new is greeted with caution and takes a long time to be accepted.
There are few extraordinary things, but I dare say that The Tap Tap is one of them.
The impression of someone who sees us for the first time is clearly compassion, it is a natural reaction...
But compassion is totally superfluous because people with disabilities are not abandoned beings who suffer and for whom we should have compassion.
There are people who are capable of living a full life and developing themselves, provided, of course, that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something goes well for people with disabilities, then it is not only an advance for them, but for society as a whole.
Did it help that you are a demanding boss, as many people describe you?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be rigorous in many aspects and demand a certain discipline.
I think it is completely normal.
Some people arrive with a romantic vision and their heads in the clouds and when they find out that they have to attend two days of rehearsals, go to the preparatory test and spend a lot of time traveling and at concerts, the initial euphoria quickly leaves them.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and achieve something.
The Tap Tap Tap group currently has twenty members.
How many of them were already there at the beginning of 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group, people come and go, it can't be helped.
Whoever has the will and the desire will always find open doors.
