Poland and the cosmos.
Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA at last week's meeting of ministers of European Space Agency countries. It is the second ESA member country from the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on November 12, 2008).
Poland started an intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the agency's project commission.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flight before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. Šternfeld's lecture at the Warsaw astronomical observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics."
The young engineer's ideas (born 1905) left the audience indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one to show interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, he was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when one of the craters on the hidden face of the moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a dresina was built in Poland that was to be fitted with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is not known who the author of the proposal was, nor are the details of the project known.
It is unclear whether the rocket was to be used for dresin startup or for braking.
The information on this dresina is limited to that collected in the press at the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to focus on missiles.
The research was funded by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the material preserved, it is evident that the research has reached the stage of practical evidence.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, research was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric fighter missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki, was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was in charge of all projects on missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the outbreak of war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, the society is referred to for the first time with four very extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
One of them, by Prof. M. Subotowicze, proposed the creation of a company dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to become a member of the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of the same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) sounding rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket on which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and was first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 air tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket under development was to be the subject of actual scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have an apogee of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high altitude wind.
However, in 1962, work was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other in the space available for scientific apparatus.
On the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for volume was 0.4 liters, on the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and on the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum apogee in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Instituto Aéreo, and its first aerial tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km altitude.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the COSPAR national committee two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the cosmic space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remek.
Suspension of the law on social work is not the solution.
Last week the constitutional court suspended the social work law.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
Of course, it will be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of more economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labor costs (wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, by importing cheap goods, tries to close the gap and for this purpose "drives down" the competitor's price in order to gain the largest share of the market and thus increase its profit margin.
On a large scale it means, for most entrepreneurs, moving production abroad, buying cheaper there or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labor is higher than in other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and, therefore, is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the state's social spending necessarily increases.
This situation leads to a total lack of interest on the part of businessmen in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damage they have caused in their eagerness to make profits.
The situation is so universally known that there is no need to present specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of these countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially lowering the social level of their own population and, in this way, attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population without regard to social decline.
This is particularly evident in changes to existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other hand, through the restricted entitlement of employees in terms of labor rights.
The result is growing poverty along with widening gaps between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years now, there have been food drop-off points in Germany for poor people who cannot support themselves through their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of assistance has now reached one million.
In the context of the increasing competitiveness of the German economy, a rather frequent case occurs: people employed on such low wages that the state has to pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind was made public in connection with the situation of auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament.
The austerity measures of practically all the southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation. People, under pressure from an abysmal decline in their social status, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to eke out a meager existence on the fringes of society, in the hope that private investment capital will one day arrive in the country.
Is it necessary to ask where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty is either passed from one country to another or never comes at all, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny fraction of a European wage.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim ad nauseam that the state should not contribute capital to the economy, that running the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends tooth and nail the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by meddling in control.
Next, it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence with its selfishness the political course and, therefore, the whole state.
In this case the answer is clearly yes.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the area of corruption, in mutual favors, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany the situation is as follows: state ministries, in the absence of financial means, commission private law firms, which are often linked to industry, to draft legislation.
Such bills are then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups representing their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation quickly find themselves in a situation like the one described by Appianos in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the Time of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state had been disintegrating for some time and the administrations were forcibly occupied".
In exchange for bribes, illegitimately obtained favors and help in financing stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption spread unimpeded and people went to the polls with their votes prearranged".... "there were no people of character who aspired to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was without consuls for eight months".... "There began to be serious talk that the only remedy for such a serious situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man"..... Although Appianos was thinking of Pompeii, Caesar came to power and transformed democracy forever into autocracy.
The conclusion, as in ancient times, is that today's society is based on ill-considered preferences for individual benefit without regard for common interests.
Private capital is not capable, in its essence, of understanding and claiming the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is the same as then, an unprecedented decline of the elite, with no effort to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems in favor of a liberal type of democracy, as a definite pause, waiting for the next coup.
The truly shattering fact is that the current elite completely ignores the loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, the social and humanitarian catastrophes we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them in ancient and more recent history.
Suspension of the public procurement law is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure of economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution lies in concrete socio-political reforms that strengthen both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society to the benefit of the state.
