Argo Movie: If it gets raw, call Hollywood
In November 1979 a group of Islamist student demonstrators occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlevi, who after the revolution fled to the U.S., the country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation did not offer any positive prospects: it could not afford to throw the shah overboard, since, if it did so, it would jeopardize the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, was not within their reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was subsequently further intensified by the failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government's negotiating intervention.
In the U.S., his fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck thematizes an episode of this story, which reaped a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up at the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
CIA, in collaboration with Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, aided by a rather extravagant cover story: they left on Canadian passports, as members of a film crew scouting locations in the country for the filming of a science fiction blockbuster.
Combination of genres
The plan drawn up by "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez required the collaboration of Hollywood.
To make the lie look true, the film project was written about in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictitious production company even had a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from Tony Mendez's recollections.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode gone wrong, a hoax (an example can be the Ocean's Eleven series).
The film is a combination of moods. On the one hand we find well-documented sequences from Tehran. In the credits sequence, emblematic photographs from the time of the events are shown, which were captured in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this respect.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes, somewhat lighter, marked by irony and slight exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions: men in suits analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to reboot his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been the object of ridicule, has become a respectable director and his acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Goodbye Little One, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film in which the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
Likewise, the sensitivity to capture the atmosphere of the place was a characteristic that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck proves it in Argo, where Tehran is "shot" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of true events. The introductory sequence of the embassy seizure is impressive for its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, conveys the emotion of the bewilderment and lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the impostor team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And he manages quite well. Sometimes he adds something to reality: here it doesn't all come out so elegantly (the scene in which he stalks the crisis at the Tehran airport, the detour of a call to America and the wild search after his trail turn into madness).
Argo's weakness is the lack of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are by no means the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses a little bit of dramatic flair, but it is a film that can be followed with moderate interest, appreciating its execution and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But for it to collapse, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a true story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services can be, it is enough.
Rules for balloon, banana and circus inflation
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which every year presents a survey on the most absurd bank fees, has now decided to announce the contest on "the most absurd regulation or ideas from the EU workshop".
"It occurred to us after the latest development, the EU plans to approve a 40 percent quota for women in management positions in large European companies," explained Právo Patrik Nacher, the survey's organizer.
Among the absurdities nominated is, for example, the recent decision of the European court to unify insurance policies between men and women.
Until now, women have benefited from better prices on life insurance because they objectively represent a lower risk.
"Other amazing ideas from the EU workshop can be proposed by people until the end of this year."
The election will take place at the end of February 2013," said Nacher.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the mandatory addition of biocomponents to fuel which, as a result, damages the environment; another ban is the use of mercury thermometers for life only because they contain a small amount of a hazardous substance or the guideline on the size of hen cages, which has contributed to the considerable increase in the price of eggs this year.
The factual prohibition of the use of the expression "butter spread" or the withdrawal of the classic light bulb from stores has been criticized.
A quality banana should have a length of 14 centimeters.
The Union's apparatus takes such decisions often under pressure from one or another business or industrial lobby, whose demands in Brussels are usually defended by a state or group of states (the Czech Republic, even with the threat of a veto, is asserting the demands of its banks).
Lobbying interests were behind the demand, for example, that the highest quality bananas in the EU must be at least 14 centimeters long and must not have "abnormal curvatures".
The European Commission defended itself by saying that it was only seeking to harmonize national standards that had not been homogenized to date, which only complicated their commercialization.
The rules referring to fruit and vegetables in the EU, despite opposition from some states, have been relaxed on the grounds that the existing directive leads to food waste.
The candidate to win the poll could be last year's EU prescription according to which it is mandatory to warn that children under 8 years of age are not allowed to inflate inflatable balloons without adult supervision.
The EU referred here to an American study according to which, when it comes to toys, balloons are the leading cause of infant death by suffocation.
A similar restriction is also in force for the use of cue sticks by children up to 14 years of age.
Curious occurrences are born even in our country
Equally absurd is the regulation concerning European civil servants: anyone who has any official function in the EU cannot use the name Macedonia. In order not to offend the sensibilities of Greece, one should speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The Bankovnípoplatky.com server, in collaboration with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, nominated in the survey, among some absurd proposals mentioned above, the Union's prescription on the volume of food supplies on the territory of a member state.
The EU determined the maximum volumes of food supplies that can be found on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our entry into the EU.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the volume established for canned mushrooms, which resulted in the threat of a substantial fine.
The organizers of the survey were also interested in the idea of paying those countries that do not have access to the sea and the idea of providing a subsidy for grant applications.
These kinds of ideas did not originate in Brussels but in Prague.
"We are at a disadvantage because we are landlocked.
We are asking the European Union for compensation," the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) said in autumn 2004.
He argued this with the fact that our country produced a lot of cereal and, as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, the state had full warehouses and had to export it.
According to Palas, since the Czech Republic is far from seaports, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
In the end, the European Commission was willing to help the Czech Republic and organized a public tender for the purchase of grain from landlocked countries.
The grant to receive a subsidy was proposed to municipalities by the Ministry for Local Development headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU). Specifically, it is intended for the drafting of applications for grants from Brussels.
EU: Rare prescriptions are an exception
While the guidelines of the member states are often the target of criticism, the EU's efforts in terms of regulations and also more effective functioning and development throughout the Union are, according to several experts, more deserving of recognition.
According to experts, the most serious problem is, for example, the collection of EU subsidies for projects that have nothing to do with deepening European integration, but which the member states have secured in budget negotiations.
The Czechs, like other EU countries, are also sensitive to the fight for the right to the designation of origin of their traditional products, although our country has not always been victorious in these struggles.
The Czechs, after six years of disputes with Germans and Austrians, successfully defended the designation of origin of Olomouc curd cheese, but had to change the name of the national rum, whose tradition in our country dates back to the 19th century, to "tuzemák".
Only products made from sugar cane distillate can be called rum, but not those made from sugar beet.
In the official list of EU protected designations of origin, along with the world-famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, marzipan from the German town of Lübeck or Parma ham, there are already, for example, Karlovy Vary cookies, Pohořelice and Třeboň carp and even the Žatec variety of hops.
As protected EU maras, they can be proud of the gingerbread from Pardubice and the wafers from Hořice v Podkrkonoší.
People want me to save the republic, but I am an amateur, says Okamura
Mr. Senator, how did it occur to you to run for President?
It is not about being a senator or president.
If everything were fine in our country, then I would not run for office.
But I can no longer bear to see how people have been stealing in the last twenty years in our country, how thieves go unpunished, how taxes are increased and the retirement age is raised.
He had no ambitions to be a politician.
When I see something I don't like, I try to find a solution to change it.
And since I am already forty years old and my candidacy is independent, the only chance I have to change things is to run for senator or president.
To the Senate he has already arrived, but soon after he has set out on the road to the presidency.
Isn't he turning his back on those people who voted for him?
I always said that my candidacy for the presidency depended on the results in the senate elections.
I later specified that if I was elected senator, I would run for the presidency.
But my goal is not the function; the function is the tool with which I can realize my own ideas.
That is why I need the greatest possible influence and the strongest possible mandate.
The problem is not just that we are a nation that we criticize in the bar or in front of the television, but that we trample on anyone who wants to initiate change.
Added to this are the media, which discredit you and confuse freedom of expression with the freedom to lie.
It is said of me that I have bribed journalists or that I have been an advisor to Jiří Paroubek.
Let's talk about your ideas.
It is presented to the presidential fight with financial theses and criminal responsibilities of politicians and the declaration of property over twenty million.
To do so, the law must be changed.
As president he does not have this competence and only the senate as a whole can propose laws.
How do you want to solve it?
As a citizen, I was part of a group that lobbied for the guide profession to be recognized as self-employment, and we succeeded.
The problem is in politics: if someone comes up with a good proposal, whether from the right or the left, it is rejected on purpose and this affects the citizens.
As an independent candidate, I have a greater potential to obtain the support of all parliamentary groups.
Without pigeonholing or party dogmas, I have the capacity to be able to choose something from each party that is best for our country and apply it.
Do you consider yourself more of a right-winger or a left-winger?
From the Czech point of view, I have the impression that people consider me more left-wing.
For me it doesn't matter, whether I'm a little left or a little right.
What matters to me is that we move forward.
I don't care if someone is right-wing or left-wing, I want to bring people together.
I always openly support any good solution, regardless of whether the proposal comes from KSČM or ODS and, likewise, I will be against bad ideas.
It is a joke when it is said that you are a populist.
But aren't you proving it by what you say?
When you create a business plan for your company, you also have certain goals and ideals.
And you try to get close to them.
There will be those who call it populism, but all the proposals I am talking about are already working in the world or well-known experts are talking about them.
But without the support of parliament he is left with only slogans.
And with that he cannot survive in politics in the long run.
Or do you think that if you go to people and talk to them, you will get, for example, criminal and financial liability?
I have no other choice.
To convince politicians, journalists and civil society and try to get them on my side to achieve it.
If elected president, there would be no problem in organizing a live television broadcast in which he would ask the leaders of the parliamentary parties to legitimize criminal and financial responsibility for politicians, civil servants, judges and state prosecutors.
And, eventually, they would have to communicate why they do not want it.
If there is a strong character who points out the disputes, pressure can be brought to bear on the political scene.
Take for example the direct election of the president, which has been an achievement of public pressure.
At the same time I affirm that I am only an amateur, I am neither a genius nor an intellectual.
For my opinions and ideals I try to seek allies.
I have just started in politics and I am trying to get as much support as possible for my program.
I try to take things forward myself, but in case it doesn't work out, in six years I will quit and go back to the private sector.
It sounds a bit like Okamura is going to save the Czech Republic.
I am no savior.
I know that with one person I do nothing, so I have visited a number of well-known personalities, in case they might be encouraged to run for the senate.
I went to see Radim Jančura, but he refused because he had a lot of work.
For my part, I have at least supported investigative journalist Jana Lorencová, who brought light heating oil frauds to light.
I applied on the basis that people are really dissatisfied, now I'm in the balance.
Sixty percent of the population did not go to the polls and, those who did, voted for establishment representatives.
In the Senate there are two of us from the independent sector.
The people elected the senate, so it will be complicated to achieve changes.
However, I will defend my own ideas, such as the direct election of mayors or governors.
Are you considering forming your own party?
I have not yet considered it because I do not have the time to do so, to check the spotless past of each of the potential party members, nor do I have the money.
I have no money even for the campaign for the presidency, in my transparent account there are only 20,000 kronor.
No money?
You talk about property declarations, what is yours like?
I estimate my private property at about 60 million.
In Prague I have a plot of land valued at 25 million, an apartment valued at ten million, another apartment valued at eight million, a collection of works of art worth ten million, an Aston Martin worth about 3.5 million and a Škoda Superb valued at one million, and in the account I have a couple of million.
By the way, I have an Aston Martin because it was my childhood dream. I always liked James Bond, who drove this car, was gallant with women and, at the same time, fought against evil and injustice.
He drives an Aston Martin, his property is valued at 60 million and he has no campaign cash?
You say you want to change the republic but you don't want to put too much money on your side.
Not very convincing.
I don't have $15 million for the campaign.
Do I have to go into debt?
I have already put 2.5 million into the campaign.
The fact that I don't have any sponsors shows that there is not much interest in my program.
And I have no obligation to pay for the campaign out of my own pocket.
Campaign expenses essentially cover what I will receive as a senator's salary.
But I could not live on it. For example, I couldn't pay for my son's English school, which costs 30,000 kronor a month.
If I only wanted to make money, then I would not run for office.
So you will continue with your business activity in order to make a living?
Didn't you say before that you were going to stop this activity?
This has nothing to do with a higher salary.
As promised, I have partly stopped my activities.
For example, my travel agency representative will become my replacement in the spring.
People would want him to be the Samaritan to save the republic.
But I also need to live on something.
How much do you usually earn monthly as an entrepreneur?
Between 200,000 and 400,000, which I continue to earn.
If I were president, then I would quit business.
