Architectural firm MVRDV proves that real adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the recently completed "book mountain" - 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and there's finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby passing by on the street.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company located near the library, notes, "Plus, the building is nice."
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have the Internet, tablets and e-books.
Nobody goes into those old-fashioned libraries for fun, do they?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town on the outskirts of Rotterdam that barely merits a fleeting visit, holds the dubious honor of a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counteract this shameful situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so it was that policy makers decided that there was only one way to improve the statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas of the Dutch architectural firm MVRDV, a master of the art of bar diagrams and responsible for buildings that are both amusing and cynical, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked around in bewilderment and shrugged their shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size in a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here it is, my proposal for the Spijkenisse book mountain, the so-called `Boekenberg'".
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is standing on the planned site.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with a subway parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential buildings and townhouses.
In early November the book mountain was awarded the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
Thus, the small town lacking in history, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall with a white façade that looks more like a dairy, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long road to the book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheese factory.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountain massif, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy on the eye, the annealed brick floor and elegant lampposts unmistakably support the library's public status.
The urban environment is perfect.
Looking up you can see the park benches, the dogs and the children playing soccer.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Usually the book shelves are arranged along the facade and in the center opens up a huge dark room that is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to turn the classic spatial configuration upside down and move the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention should be made of the black shelves that serve as wall cladding, parapet and railing at the same time.
Sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even the most up to date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project leader in the city of Spijkenisse.
And so it was that one day, on a Frisian farm, we came across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, a plastic fabric only a few millimeters thick has been used in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands as a base to support the roots of crops.
It is an inexpensive and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, until four centimeter thick sheets were obtained.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mixture of new car and sneaker.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain, the reward awaits us: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but you can also enjoy some tasty Dutch croquettes and its ficus trees planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant environment while maintaining the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"Although it is hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is provided by geothermal energy.
Despite the fact that the book mountain is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
Huge wooden trusses across the glass facade provide shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is a matter of automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Likewise, professor of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She describes the "Boekenberg" as the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
This is intended to fill, for the time being, the optical gaps in a library that does not yet have a complete archive; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has caught on.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain bond with this building.
Everyone knows that your book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there for decoration.
In this way, the MVRDV studio has achieved success in this discipline, which in specialized jargon is known as "creating an identity".
The town of Spijkenisse has written a piece of literary history.
Regardless of how young and uneducated she may be.
Finally, a starting point to shape their identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more leading role".
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, this puts Berlin in a rather tricky diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier in the week, Germany hinted that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories UN observer state status.
In the end, however, Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, because of the country's special relationship with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the U.S. position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, that's right.
This is because it is currently reorienting its foreign policy away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that the Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans are therefore at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but are not used to doing so.
I think they are still feeling out what their role will be, but they have already started on the road to a "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to that of countries such as France or Great Britain.
What does "normal" foreign policy mean in concrete terms from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is strongly motivated by economic policy, i.e. exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers and for that reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance taken on the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason, it must be careful not to alienate itself from Arab public opinion and Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I wouldn't read too much into it since it's not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the U.S. by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic rupture as in the case of Libya.
This may have earned Germany a certain amount of respect.
At the end of the day, all this has only demonstrated that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international player and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe there are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
In contrast, the U.S. has come out clearly in favor of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the U.S. and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of U.S. domestic policy.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly shows great understanding for the European position.
But, because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot defend this position in public.
