"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a brand known worldwide and so is Polo Ralph Lauren.
But what is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is a name that is officially registered in China but has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the real eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then, it is not clear that they will be given the nod.
"Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China," says Thomas Pattloch, an attorney with Taylor Wessing, a law firm specializing in protective rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case arrives on my desk.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters in order to register their trademarks.
Thus, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada, Prada-Kny is registered as Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copying each other in the same way, as has happened to the sporting goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet in which he keeps entries from the Beijing trademark office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the Zegna DF Puma trademark, an artificial name that also made use of the Ermenegildo Zegna fashion house.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are large multi-storey department stores dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch's cases are of a different nature. On behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to profit from a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or companion brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
which refers to women who have "fished" for a rich man.
Chinese authorities do not feel guilty
"It's detrimental to business, you have to fight it," Pattloch demands.
"The brand takes on water, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage to the image is enormous."
The financial losses and legal costs of the affected sectors are in the millions, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year, China is the third largest and fastest growing luxury goods market.
However, obtaining the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in the trademark registry is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
Proceedings can take up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch speaks of cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because so much time had elapsed that the name that was the subject of the lawsuit had already become a "market reality."
"If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarizer because the process has damaged the plagiarizer's brand in China," Pattloch points out.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been taken over by German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
This is why to this day the Chinese can still use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo's buyer, Geely, initially used a blue-and-white logo that was highly reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to change it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China against imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo depicted a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing acknowledges that they have had difficulties in 2010 due to shortages of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, "the labor emergency situation returned to normal".
As a result, the number of unprocessed claims has been reduced by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims are still pending resolution.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As usual in China, the figures are staggering.
Last year the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million applications for trademark protection, almost a third more than in 2010.
This would be a new record and means that China leads the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, according to the trademark office.
This also seems to be the case for the number of valid logos, which amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, they reportedly pocketed 1.8 billion yuan in royalties.
Put another way, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family-owned company Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese imitator.
While the Germans have succeeded in stopping the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the copycat has managed to secure Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
"We have brought this situation on ourselves because surnames are not protected in Germany," says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the Munich-based company's appeal.
In the next two instances Freudenberg has been upheld, but the opposing side is still fighting today.
You have to be very, very careful
Now the case has reached the doors of the Superior Court of Justice, where it is still pending resolution.
Wentzler is confident that the matter can be resolved favorably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that "the procedure is extremely costly, both in terms of money and time".
Internal costs are difficult to estimate; the corporate archive has had to review files up to 100 years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposing party a "six-figure sum in euros" with the aim of reaching an amicable settlement, but was unsuccessful.
"It shows how much we care," notes Wentzler.
The dangers lurking in the Far East even threaten to affect Europe,
particularly if the imitators secure there the rights to unprotected trademarks.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register the name Freudenberg in Germany for shoes and leather products.
The group has long since left this commercial field, but nevertheless managed to prevent registration.
"You have to be extremely careful," says Wentzler.
Both he and attorney Pattloch advise German companies to be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark law; what is needed is "to register everything that can be protected in China as well," as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the issue can be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, should Freudenberg lose the last round of his particular battle, he would then have to pay the opposing party licensing fees for his own name, as Wentzler explains.
Either that or we would be driven out of the market in the segment in question.
World AIDS Day: Dance, Sing, Help
Imbongi choir rehearses in Heidelberg and AIDS orphans rejoice in Swaziland
The story of a bond capable of overcoming much more than 8,733 kilometers of distance.
First you start with the dance: cowboy boots, basketball shoes, high heels and loafers search for the beat on the parquet floor, and quickly find it.
One, two, three, four.
Only then do the voices of the singers (alto, bass, tenor and soprano) slowly begin to rise, swirling, hindering and following each other.
And Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old director, threatens to get almost out of hand as he tries to bring order with his forceful and gentle gestures.
It is Monday afternoon and in the music room of the Heidelberg Institute for Medical Psychology the Imbongi choir is rehearsing a new song.
The fifty singers, ranging in age from 23 to 69, from the human geneticist to the householder, have also arrived.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy piece, each voice of the choir has a different text and moreover in a barely known foreign language: Zulu, a language spoken by eleven million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and in some areas of Swaziland.
Help for self-help
According to an estimate by UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS program, approximately 34 million people worldwide are infected with the HIV virus.
23.5 million of them live in southern Africa.
There are 245,000 AIDS orphans in Swaziland.
More than 40% of the population is already HIV-positive.
Voices for Africa has found sponsors in Germany for 180 AIDS orphans from the village of Esitjeni.
Seventy of them attend high school.
For 15 or 20 euros a month you can sponsor a child.
This contribution will cover school tuition, uniform and will guarantee one hot meal a day at the Gogo Center.
Imbongi means "storyteller" or "panegyrist" in Zulu.
No one in this room can speak this Bantu language fluently, but they can sing.
For ten years this choir has been rehearsing songs in this soft foreign language that sometimes transports them to their place of origin: southern Africa.
8,733 kilometers as the crow flies from Heidelberg, in the northeastern part of the kingdom of Swaziland, there is a village called Esitjeni that depends on the voices of this German choir.
Forty percent are infected
Approximately 2,000 people live there, some still in simple mud and straw huts, a large number of them children.
More than 300 no longer have parents because they have succumbed to AIDS.
Esitjeni is a small example of what ails Swaziland: the highest AIDS infection rate and the lowest life expectancies in the world, according to Unicef.
Circumcision, a practice that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by half, is frowned upon by the population.
More than 40% of Swazilanders are carriers of the immunodeficiency virus, and dying in their thirties has become commonplace.
During a joint trip to Africa in the spring of 2005 the choir discovered this remote village, but what they saw above all were many children on the streets who lacked not only the protection of their parents, but also the basics: food, clothing and education.
Without a school diploma, the chances in a poor country are more than slim.
In the beginning it was only the private commitment of a few that made it possible for a child to go to school and enjoy a hot meal a day. All this for a few euros.
However, a year later the choir founded the association "Voices for Africa" which has since then been professionally caring for AIDS orphans in Esitjeni.
Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
STDs of bacterial origin include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhea.
The most common viral STDs are AIDS, human papillomavirus, genital herpes and hepatitis.
Crabs and scabies are among the STDs transmitted by parasites.
What are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur more frequently in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five cases of syphilis in Germany originate from sexual contact between men.
In the case of heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydial infections, trichomonas, human papillomavirus, candidiasis (fungus) and gonorrhea.
HIV infection among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively low; however, approximately 20% of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydial infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In our country, the human papilloma virus is also added to the most common diseases among young people.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been on a downward trend since 2007.
Approximately 2,700 cases were registered in 2011.
This is one tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort during urination, discharge, abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
They often do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore go undetected.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not offer 100% protection.
Some sexually transmitted disease pathogens can also be transmitted through soil infections and physical contact.
For this reason, experts recommend regular medical examinations, especially if you change sexual partners frequently.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any late consequences can be avoided.
Through collaborations, donations and, last but not least, from the fees the choir charges for its performances all over Germany, they manage to raise quite a lot of money.
