To encourage cultural exchange, the Imbongi choir travels every two or three years through southern Africa singing songs that speak of melancholy, fighting spirit, hope and confidence in the black race, songs that many in the southernmost tip of the African continent still remember from the apartheid era.
A bus full of white people singing songs in a black language; so much recognition not only brings an excellent atmosphere and a lot of joy, but has also managed to bring a couple of tears to the eyes of the occasional rabid border soldier.
The trip always takes them to Esitjeni, where the singers visit the sponsored children.
Although this small town hardly appears on maps, it is well known in the Ezulweni River valley.
