Drink butter daily and live 168 years
In southern Azerbaijan many people reach biblical ages.
There is even a museum dedicated to longevity.
A search for footprints in a country where 97-year-olds are still considered young.
In southern Azerbaijan many people reach biblical ages.
There is even a museum dedicated to longevity.
A search for footprints in a country where 97-year-olds are still considered young.
The journey through the mountainous region of Talysh could be described as wild and romantic.
The minibus rumbles along the winding road past forested hills, fast-flowing rivers and the simple houses of local farmers.
Everything is green and juicy, you might even think you are in the Black Forest.
However, we are in the southernmost part of Azerbaijan; from here the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
Here live the "talyshi", a people about whom not much is known, apart from the fact that they are fluent in Persian and Azeri and that they are very long-lived.
Our final destination is Lerik.
This small town boasts a perhaps too massive architecture designed in the Soviet era and that does not seem to fit at all in such a picturesque mountainous landscape.
European tourists hardly ever come here, as the journey from the capital of Azerbaijan, Baku, is too tiring.
It takes eight hours to travel the 323 kilometers that separate the two urban centers because the road is one-way.
The astonishing wealth that the country enjoys thanks to the Caspian Sea oil has not yet reached this remote region.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
"Baku became famous in May on the occasion of the Eurovision Song Contest and next year we will hold the World's Oldest People Festival," Fatulayeva notes.
She is the director of the Longevity Museum, perhaps the only one in the world.
Documented here are the lives of eight dozen local talyshis who are over 100 years old. Fatulayeva points to a black and white image.
This is my grandfather, who lived 120 years.
A son died at the age of 136 years.
However, the undisputed star of the museum is the sheep herder Şirali Müslümov, who seems to have lived 168 years.
However, there is no birth certificate to certify this.
And if we take into account that the oldest documented man lived 122 years, it seems that Müslümov's age is rather suspicious.
"She was born in the region in 1805 and died in 1973," Fatulayeva explains.
The man was married three times and had 23 children. He apparently still had time to conceive one more daughter at the age of 136.
Has Şirali Müslümov then mistaken his age by a couple of decades?
However, Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, has also heard about the advanced age of this Central Asian inhabitant.
"In some regions of China, Japan or in the Hunza Valley in Pakistan there are also very old people living," says Scholz, "even in Sardinia there are many older men."
Due to the lack of documentation, it is impossible to provide scientific proof of age, especially since there is no civil registry.
Everyday glasses full of melted butter
It is a fact that, surprisingly often, the inhabitants of the region around Lerik often reach a biblical age.
There are currently 20 people over 100 years of age.
Why do so many elderly people live here in the south?
Azeri tour guide Farid Mugimzadeh explains that these are the special genes of the talyshis.
The museum's director, Ms. Fatulayeva, believes instead that the cause lies in the diet.
However, from a nutritional point of view, it does not seem logical that precisely the high-calorie diet of the Talyshi, who love meat, bread and above all dairy products and many of whom, in addition, drink a glass of melted butter daily, is so healthy.
Or maybe it is the natural way of life that keeps people young? In Cengemiran, a small settlement not far from the town of Lerik lives Rubaba Mirzayeva.
At 97 years of age, he is relatively young by the standards of these latitudes.
Mirzayeva, who claims 143 descendants, lives in a simple wooden house typical of the entire Caucasus region.
Sitting on the floor, she tirelessly moves a huge tub of butter.
Eight people live under one roof, including one of Mirzayeva's sons and a daughter, both of whom became grandparents some time ago.
Also jumping up and down are two small children.
In the kitchen they prepare tea for the guests, a tea served in typical convex glasses.
Mirzayeva's teeth are white and perfectly aligned and under her scarf she hides two long braids of dark blonde hair that her son proudly reveals to us.
I have always washed my hair with milk, so it has never fallen out and has kept its color.
"I've never used a shampoo either," Mirzayeva says.
The pension is enough to live on
He has always eaten only what he produced on his own farm: tomatoes, potatoes and peas.
In all my life I have never gone shopping in a supermarket.
Then she tells us about her husband, who was in the army.
The worst was the period after World War II.
However, everything got back on track when the "dear father", Heydar Aliyew, took control of the situation.
This kind of propaganda sounds strange coming from the mouth of an older woman.
However, in Azerbaijan the cult of the father figure of the nation, who runs his country like a dictator, knows no bounds.
He remained in power until 2003, when he passed the baton to his son Ilham.
At least the elderly in Azerbaijan do not know what poverty is.
Mirzayeva is paid 230 manat (about the same amount in euros) as a monthly pension, an amount on which one can live well considering the situation here.
And perhaps Mirzayeva's gray-haired son is right: "in our culture the elders are highly respected".
They live in a big family, are loved, receive all the necessary care and are happy.
As if this were not enough reason to stay alive for many years...
