Norwegian rakfisk: the world's smelliest fish?
Norway's five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country's success has something to do with its appetite for extremely smelly fish?
Take a series of excessively cured cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a mountain of dirty, wet soccer clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You can then smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway's delicacies.
I am located in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It is snowy. The scenery is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
Rakfisk is salted trout that is left to ferment in water for, depending on how smelly you prefer it, up to a year.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival held here in Fagernes dedicated to this most, shall we say, captivating delicacy.
"You eat it raw and then drink a glass of aquavit in one gulp," says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also what is known as the "Rakfisk General," who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we go we see people eating this fish, which is kept in small buckets, and drinking large quantities of the beverage in one gulp.
"Some people like aquavit better than rakfisk," Havard says.
Drinking can kill the odor.
I try some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it close to your nose, it's not bad; it's not much different than a portion of sushi that has traveled a few miles by bus.
Rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, when poverty was rife in Norway and when, before refrigeration existed, fish was stored during the autumn submerged in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is well fermented, it is taken out and, obviously with the senses inactive due to the alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, emigrating mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly; more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a comprehensive system of social services.
A stream of inhabitants from Sweden, the old rival and until not too long ago much richer than Norway, arrives in this country to work.
The rakfisk is considered something important, an essential, if rather smelly, part of Norway's past.
It is among the most expensive dishes you can buy.
But, in fact, everything is expensive. A glass of beer or a sandwich costs a whopping 10€ ($14) each.
Norway is not usually on the international news agenda and most Norwegians like it that way.
People here are still unwilling to pronounce the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who gunned down and murdered 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as "the July 22 event."
Norwegians find it extremely hard to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own would be capable of such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway's current wealth is the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil is not the only reason we are doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, as she passes around trays of rakfisk and who, with her long blonde hair and striking blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
"We are, as you say, prudent people."
His English, like that of most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to show off, we don't like ostentation."
Norway has managed its oil wealth very carefully; all but a small percentage of the money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone else was wasting money they didn't have during the years leading up to the financial crisis around the world, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we're happy," says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with a lighthearted laugh.
I'm in the snow standing in line to get something to eat; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now an elk burger is certainly something different and quite succulent to savor.
But at night, that smelly fish returns.
The hotel where I'm staying is one of many venues that hosts a rakfisk dinner where diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the most nostril-testing fish.
A television has gone live with a presenter wearing a bow tie and surrounded by plates of rakfisk.
It looks like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There is laughter and applause.
A man falls off his chair, perhaps overcome by aquavit.
Or maybe it's the fumes from all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a rough start
As Mexico's incoming President Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant discusses the challenges the new president will face and the different expectations of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city that, under the best of circumstances, is already congested as it is, a steel fence has been in place since Monday, cutting off several of the main roads leading into the city and causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The objective, however, was not to prevent workers from being able to reach their workplace, but to prevent protesters from being able to reach parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto, will receive the presidential sash and take office.
You face a complicated task.
Mexico has been doing well economically under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, but the country is mired in a drug war that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government has a great commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence," Mr. Peña Nieto explained earlier this week to U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office.
"I am going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal."
Prior to rubbing elbows with the U.S. president, Mr. Peña's previous political experience was as governor of his home state of Mexico.
A densely populated and fast-growing state surrounding the capital; opinions about the new leader are divided in this territory where he used to move.
A sincere man
In the bucolic town of Valle del Bravo, for example, he is fondly remembered.
