Hidden under elevated stretches of highway, it is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems of the municipality are also hard and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called in to assist in the fight against drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is particularly severe.
On a deserted plot of land next to a garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left abandoned in just the last two years.
More than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was governor, a rate far higher than that of Ciudad Juarez, unfortunately notorious for its violence and a place that is synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
Mr. Peña Nieto's critics say, at best, that he failed to address the problem of femicide while in office.
Critics accuse his administration of turning a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the rundown neighborhood, Irinea Buendia has to struggle to hold back tears as she shows me photographs of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her partner murdered her.
"When I got to his house, it looked as if his body had been cleaned," Mrs. Buendía recalls.
"There were signs that she had been beaten and rigor mortis had already set in."
As her mother tells the story, a photograph of Mariana looks out from the walls, next to a cross with a single word on it: Justice.
Yet that is exactly what the family says they have been denied.
"The state authorities have treated me as if I were an old gossip, a troublemaker, a complainer.
What they want is for you to simply accept what they say and shut up."
"But that can't be the case when there have been so many irregularities and so much negligence," he says.
The presidential sash that President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will come with an enormous responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crime in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has promised to make them a priority during his term.
"I hope he is the same kind of president he was when he was governor," says PRI deputy Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
However, that is exactly what the families of the Ciudad Neza victims fear the most.
Bradley Manning did not report abuse, prosecutors say
Prosecutors seek to address allegations of abuse by Bradley Manning while in prison
Trial focuses on Manning's time at Quantico military prison in Virginia
Defense wants case dismissed on grounds that Manning's imprisonment was harsh
The Army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors sought to show Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report the mistreatment he now alleges he suffered while in military detention.
During prosecutorial cross-examination of Manning at a pretrial hearing at Ft. Meade, Maryland, prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein asserted that records of weekly visits by unit officers that Manning received during nine months of detention at Quantico, Virginia, show no allegations about his treatment.
The questioning, which took place during a hearing following a defense motion to dismiss the case on the grounds that his incarceration had been harsh and that it had been punishment enough, came a day after Manning had testified that he had considered suicide while in custody.
The Army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
WikiLeaks later published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled out after visits with Manning during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was incarcerated in maximum confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers reportedly asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When asked about the forms by Fein on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had described his treatment by orderlies as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facility in general as "very professional."
The forms show no allegations of mistreatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about his treatment, Fein said.
Manning responded that he had expressed concerns about some issues and that the visiting officers had discussed those issues and indicated that they would be addressed, but that they did not put those issues on the record.
"They were writing 'no incidences' (after discussing the problems) but that doesn't necessarily mean I hadn't mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Army Col. Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not reported the treatment he received during a January 2011 meeting with a board charged with examining suicide intentions he had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during that meeting was to obtain a reduction in the "injury prevention" regime under which he was placed.
The military said it had placed him under this restrictive regime, which is one grade below suicide watch, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was OK and (wanted) to get off injury prevention ... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being moved to the military prison located at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said that not being allowed to know what was happening to him or what was going on in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world came down to just Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning explained Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning claimed that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell for at least 21 hours and often for 23 hours unaccompanied.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from outside pointed at his eyes while he slept.
He said that if the orderlies could not see his face when he turned over at night, they would wake him up to turn over again.
Manning's attorney filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning's treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in Thursday's deposition that, after being forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell one night, he was forced during a morning roll call to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the recount.
During questioning by the judge on Friday, Manning said he inferred from the order given to him by the warden that he should drop the blanket with which he might have covered himself, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before in an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning claimed that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic from his underwear or his flip-flops to self-injure but that he had not.
Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell that night.
His lawyers are hopeful that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he went through during his time in prison and drastically reduce his sentence should he be convicted at the court martial, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to have Manning plead guilty to lesser crimes and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held in accordance with the rules that apply to any detainee in maximum custody at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperating with the enemy, unlawfully causing the release of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information, and theft of public property or records.
If convicted on all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He states that many were forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities.
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; he says they remember Mexicans from those difficult times.
Navarrette comments that Mexican-Americans are caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had barely walked down the concourse and into the immigration processing area and was already totally confused.
Signs indicated the way to two queues: one for "Mexicans" and the other for "Foreigners".
I stood there for a few seconds not sure where I should go.
Growing up in Central California, I have been called "Mexican" my whole life.
This is ethnic shorthand, in the same way that my Boston friends refer to themselves as "Irish" or my New York friends label themselves "Italian."
Later I decided to go with "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, shorthand or scripts were not necessary.
It was simply American.
I speak Spanish. Well enough to handle myself during an interview in this language.
But I don't have the vocabulary level of a native speaker and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and got in the foreigners' queue.
I thought of that moment this week when Mexican President-elect Enrique Peña Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda of the day, as always when the leaders of these two countries meet, was immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also eager to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why Mexicans are now as likely to stay in Mexico as they are to venture to the United States.
It wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create a European Union-style trading bloc in North America.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of rancor.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half of their territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not minutes, the reminders are everywhere.
So, the moment a U.S. official says anything that carries even the slightest criticism of Mexico, you start hearing complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how the Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the sons of Moctezuma go on the warpath.
And yet, for Mexico, the really challenging relationship is with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking about rancor?
There is a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it does not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that somewhere in our family tree, there was a person, maybe the father or mother or one of the grandparents, who was shut out of opportunities in Mexico and had to move north.
And most of the time that person fit a certain profile: dark skin, a low level of education, from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not to Mexico.
And, even though we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and had good jobs, we can never lose sight of the fact that what we are living is that, the American dream, and not the Mexican dream.
Our identity may not be clear at times, but our loyalty is.
It is for the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many of the Mexican ruling class elite do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us as if we were of an inferior category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In his view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have left.
And now we would not find ourselves trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came legally to the United States when she was a child, reminds me that there is this friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more solidly who they are and the latter are bothered by it.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she considers herself part of both countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel they are part of neither.
We love to listen to the Mexican group Los Tigres del Norte, but also to Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of each country, but you are not rooted to any of them.
In Mexico they see us as Americans.
And in the United States we are considered Mexicans.
Now, to complicate things further, from what I learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as impromptu "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our fellow Americans how great it is to visit that country and lobby political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course...
That is not going to happen.
There is too much rancor.
And, with wage inequality, rampant corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure it is a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're going to be on your own with this idea, folks.
It is fair.
If some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for the way it treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans still resent the way their relatives were treated much, much less time ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we are more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
Ceasefire between Israel and Hamas may well be an unlikely basis for peace
Can there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
Amid the usual useless bickering over who started first, piles of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, Israel's metropolis, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But although the Israelis and Palestinians seem to be stuck in their old conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left everything in tatters whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been caught up in the regional turmoil.
Perhaps this will make their fight even bloodier than before.
However, there is reason to believe that their lethal stalemate could unravel.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism currently seems very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 holds, this week's clashes have strengthened the hawks on both sides.
Leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has taken a beating.
And despite killing some of its leaders and squeezing Gaza's 1.7 million inhabitants into one of the most miserable and populated corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to wipe out Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its implacable rivals in Fatah, the more moderate Palestinian faction.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may conclude that time is on their side.
As Islamists have been gaining influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power that had previously been Israel's closest Muslim ally, has embraced the Hamas cause. So has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf.
Exultant Hamas members say the Islamist crescent is encircling Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where the Hezbollah party-militia dominates, through Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist bent could topple Bashar Assad, all the way to Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Especially on Israel's southern flank, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and pivotal of the Arab countries, has changed the balance in the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, did not have much time for Hamas.
In contrast, the Muslim Brotherhood are first cousins of Hamas and their leaders are more dependent on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, Hamas may emerge as a protagonist that cannot be excluded, not even by Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, Israel's hardliners will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military issue is concerned, Hamas has been put in its place.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system has proven effective and many of Hamas' missiles have been destroyed.
Israelis will sleep easier... for a while.
On the diplomatic front, the United States is more assertive than ever; many European countries also blamed Hamas for initiating the latest wave of violence.
Above all, Israel has prospered. Especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets fired from Gaza have killed some 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide bombers, thanks in part to the barrier that corrodes the West Bank, the main piece of territory aspiring to become a state of Palestine, and protects Jewish settlements that continue to grow despite the fact that, under international law, they are illegal.
Mr. Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined an even more hard-line group led by Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the election on Jan. 22, is in a good position.
Why coddle those twisted Palestinians by giving them a state of their own?
If they really ruled in the West Bank, wouldn't they fire rockets just as their compatriots have done in Gaza?
It's better to have them behind that wall and give them a good whack if they raise their heads.
Perhaps the hard wing will prevail, although the Arab Spring could alter their calculations.
Even if the Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere are not too fond of Israel, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel's defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the area's superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to improve their economies.
That the pragmatic Mr. Morsi worked with Barack Obama to bring about the cease-fire bodes well and could mark the start of something.
Israelis should also think long term.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving the Palestinians of their right to self-determination means creating a powder keg that will one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and demographics worsen the situation as the Arab population increases.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to repel Hamas will pay an ever-increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from outsiders.
The solution remains the one touted by sensible people on both sides, most of the outside world and this newspaper: two states and the ceding of territory by Israel for security reasons.
The hope, small in the short term, is that the ceasefire will give a little more impetus to outsiders who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must begin to curb the flow of arms into Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented position to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with land swaps and a shared Jerusalem.
Outsider Arabs should also put pressure on Hamas and Fatah to unite.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the impending attempt to obtain virtual statehood at the UN.
Mr. Obama also has an important role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term he failed to present his own plan for peace.
Back in the White House, he seems just as reluctant to devote his attention to it.
This attitude represents a deplorable vision of the future.
A stable Middle East is of vital interest to the United States.
This implies a peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
Tobacco plain packaging law comes into force in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and diseased body parts appear on dull green packs, which are the same for all tobacco brands.
Australia's world-first tobacco and plain packaging law comes into force, replacing brand logos and colors with dull olive green packaging, gruesome images of diseased body parts and depictions of children and babies sickened by smoking parents.
With the exception of the various images and health warnings, the only difference between the packs, mandatory as of Saturday, are the brand names, all printed in a small font.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
Australia's federal government says the aim is to deter young people from smoking by removing the trappings that glamorize the habit.
Rely on studies that show that if a person has not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that he or she never will.
"You can see that children, even from a very young age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand," said federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that showed, for example, how girls related a crown logo to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and these changes will not affect multinationals' profits too much, other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry has exerted enormous pressure against the law.
Tobacco companies claimed that the law would encourage the black market in tobacco, where cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
"The legislation will carry serious unintended consequences," said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco in Australia.
The amount of tobacco brought in by counterfeiters from China and Indonesia to sell on the streets of Australia will increase.
Others say their business has benefited following the passage of the law.
Sandra Ha, of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said demand for cigarette cases and silicone covers to cover up unsightly images on packs had shot up from almost zero two months ago, when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a challenge to the law in Australia's High Court.
Ms. Ha stated that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesalers and was waiting for more stock.
"For us, it's good business."
According to experts, the potential obstacle is the popularity of social networks among the target demographic.
Following a series of Australian laws banning television advertising and sports sponsorship and forcing most retailers to keep cigarettes out of sight, tobacco marketing has moved online.
Australia has banned Internet advertising on local companies and websites, but cannot restrict it on foreign websites.
"If you market tobacco and you only have this small window left to promote your products, the online space is the most compelling place to be," said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noted an increase in brand reviews from "everyday citizens" posted on social networking websites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
One wonders if this is just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigars and has taken the trouble to make a video or if some marketing company is behind it all.
Australia's British American Tobacco indicated that the industry is more focused on what the new regulations entail than on marketing.
The industry has even paid for Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules; these countries are claiming to the World Trade Organization that trade is being unfairly restricted, despite the fact that none of these countries have significant trade volumes with Australia.
The WTO is likely to issue a ruling in mid-2013.
Plibersek said the government had been in talks with other countries that are considering similar tobacco packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to introduce mandatory images on cigarette packs.
They are currently mandatory in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in Great Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
In Australia many smokers are defiant.
"Photographs don't affect me.
I just don't listen to them".
"You take the cigar and put the pack away," says Victor El Hage as he buys a pack with the image of a tumor in his mouth.
"Honestly, there's only one reason I would quit smoking: for my daughter."
James Yu, manager of the King of the Pack tobacconist in downtown Sydney, points out that the uniform packs make it more difficult for him to place them on the shelves.
"It used to take me an hour to unwrap a delivery; now it takes me four," Yu says.
"The government should have banned tobacco altogether and then, that's it, okay, that's it, we're done and we close the store," he says as he raises his hands upward.
In a constantly connected world, it's not so bad to get a little bored.
During the Thanksgiving holiday this year, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying on had a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had lots and lots of time to think about boredom.
I'm not going to lie to you.
Spending half a day in an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is pretty boring, even if you have the means to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, not to mention the duty-free stores.
But more and more academics and child development experts are extolling the benefits of boredom.
According to them, it's okay for us and our children to be bored from time to time.
Being bored forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since, nowadays, most of us are connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits of boredom.
So, should we accept boredom in good spirits?
Yes.
And no.
But, we will talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History," published in 2011 by Yale University Press, argues, this is not the case.
"In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about boredom dating back to the 1st century AD.
We must also ask ourselves how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in so many different ways," says John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After reviewing published research and pitching the idea to a focus group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "wanting to, but not being able to, engage in an activity that fulfills you."
He states that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person is not doing something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do something.
The primary experience of boredom, he says, is "disruption of the attention process, associated with low mood and a feeling that time is passing slowly."
Boredom can sound an awful lot like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that, although they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed see the problem as their own.
Sometimes we think we are bored, when what is really happening to us is that we are having trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a journal article.
Some groups listened to an unrelated television program at full volume in the next room, others listened with the volume turned down so that it was barely audible, while the third group did not hear the audio at all.
The group that listened to the program with the volume turned down showed more boredom than the other two groups; they found it hard to concentrate, but were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you're trying to concentrate on a difficult or interesting task, attention disturbance can lead to boredom," said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the study's authors.
"On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, like detecting defective parts on a manufacturing line, distracting music can help you not get bored."
"In fact, we now know that fidgeting or doodling, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help combat boredom by making that person more physically alert."
"Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to stand still," says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it's like to be bored at some point: a plane delay, a monotonous speaker, a particularly dull movie.
But some people are more likely to be bored than others.
To help measure this, researchers developed a "boredom tendency scale" in the 1980s.
The scale includes issues such as "many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "there are so many things that interest me that I don't have time to do everything".
Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that, using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to be bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external and more varied stimulation.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of Human and Community Development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day by pager.
It found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored while in school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when not in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Prof. Larson said he did not know whether current boredom rates 21 years later would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that "adolescence is a period when boredom reaches its highest heights," largely because both children and adolescents are not given a great deal of control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question at the beginning: is it good to be bored?
Sometimes it is not, because, taken to the extreme, it can expose us to absurd physical risks, such as gambling or substance abuse as a method to combat it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this question for more than two decades.
"Boredom is the brain's way of telling you that you should be doing something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain does not always know what is most appropriate.
If you are bored and use that energy to play guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, you may be satisfied in the short term, but not in the long term.
"So, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may no longer be bored, but he won't have learned how to entertain himself or how to dose himself," says Professor Fenske.
And "that ability to dose down applies to other situations," he says.
Your child not only learns to entertain himself, but also learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we should not be too critical of him either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant buzz of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"The way we see it, we need to be bored more, but boredom is too distressing and unsettling a desire to relate it to anything worthwhile," he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to unwind and enjoy some downtime.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated," he says, "it's hard to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops."
Colorado: no briefing book for new marijuana law
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old community college student and soccer player from southeastern Colorado, is facing criminal prosecution for something that will soon be legal statewide: possession of a few rocks of marijuana and a pipe he used to smoke it.
Orozco says that one day in September, he and some friends were driving through Lamar, in the plains near the Kansas border, when they were stopped by police.
Police found marijuana in the car and some time later Orozco received a court summons for possession of drugs and related items (misdemeanors that each carry a fine of US$100) informing him of the trial date.
"They treat us like criminals," says Orozco.
And are they?
In the weeks of uncertainty following Colorado's vote to legalize possession of small amounts of marijuana for recreational use, the response in hundreds of minor drug possession cases depends less on the law than on location.
Hundreds of misdemeanor marijuana possession offenses are being overturned both here and in Washington state, where a similar measure was passed.
Police departments have stopped charging those over 21 with small-scale possession, which will be legally approved once the law has gone into effect in the coming weeks.
But Colorado's more conservative district attorneys have vowed to move forward with open marijuana possession cases and are still subpoenaing people.
At the same time, several cities, from the Denver suburbs to the western mountains, are voting to prevent newly licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
"This is all changing so fast, I don't know what's next," said Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, just east of Denver.
Regulators in Washington State are also giving the matter some thought.
And they continue to seek advice on establishing a licensing system for production, manufacturing, distribution and sales, all before the December 1, 2013 deadline.
They say that, for better or worse, Colorado is ahead of most states in regulating marijuana use, first for therapeutic purposes and now for recreational use.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so it will be a good guide," says Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Alcohol Control Commission.
But Mr. Smith admits that any one place or system can only make suggestions about what might work.
"There is no real precedent to serve as a model for us," he says.
Washington's law, called I-502, goes into effect on December 6, which also leaves a year during which to swim between two waters, as the licensing system in that state will not yet exist, but possession will be legal.
In addition, there are some tricky mechanical issues to be resolved during that period, such as how to maintain a balance between the state's requirement to provide "adequate access" to licensed marijuana and its prohibition on conducting cannabis business within 300 meters of schools, parks, children's playgrounds or children's centers.
"Nowhere will it be more difficult to locate a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metro area," says Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On Nov. 21, Oates, Aurora's police chief, sent an e-mail to his police officers informing them that the city attorney would stop bringing misdemeanor prosecutions for possession of marijuana for persons over the age of 21 and that police would stop charging such offenses "effective immediately."
Police Chief Oates said they would enforce the city's regulations governing the cultivation of marijuana for medical purposes and would continue to pursue drug dealers and traffickers.
In Weld County, in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck represents a stricter view.
After the vote, he assured that his office would continue to pursue marijuana possession cases, mainly to put pressure on users to seek treatment.
Currently, 119 people are facing charges for possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many of them have other charges.
"Our office has an obligation to prosecute those offenses that at the time they occurred were criminal," Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The response has been complicated even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana legalization initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county's largest city, no longer cite adults for possession of small amounts.
Pete Hautzinger, county district attorney, supported this decision, but also decided not to dismiss any of the pending possession cases.
"I don't consider that I am wasting my time by continuing to enforce the law until it changes," he said.
Although 55 percent of voters supported the measure, bringing recreational marijuana use into the mainstream of government and the judicial system was never considered to be easy.
The mixed reactions emerging throughout the state reveal a marked ambivalence among officials about the great environmentalist experiment in this state.
"It's a cultural barrier with district attorneys," says Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney who represents marijuana possession defendants and is a local spokesman for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Law.
"They've spent so much time taking people to court that they really still can't accept that it's legal," he said.
As the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana the same as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are poised to become the national test cases for drug legalization.
While lawyers and state officials are counting on a new frontier of legal sales, they are also anxiously awaiting guidance from the federal government, which still envisions the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Marijuana legalization advocates are hopeful that the Justice Department will relent.
Although there have been some high-profile arrests of medical marijuana patients and sellers, the federal government has mostly allowed medical marijuana businesses to exist in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
"While drug agents are not likely to kick down doors to confiscate a small bag of drugs, they will probably be reluctant to allow state-regulated stores for the sale of recreational marijuana permitted under the new law to operate," said Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration.
Several Colorado cities are not waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before Election Day, some local governments passed moratoriums on any new marijuana stores, even though it will be about a year before any of them can open.
Last week, the western city of Montrose adopted a six-month ban and is likely to approve it next week.
"We don't want to put ourselves in a situation where we authorize someone and then have a serious problem at the federal level," explained Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
"Our community voted against this amendment.
We are studying in favor of what the community voted for versus voting in favor of what the state voted for."
Many questions arise in this regard.
Petronella Wyatt: "I was bullied out of Oxford for being a Tory".
University students are not being attacked for their views only now.
I can't remember a time in my life when I wasn't dreaming of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had been to what I assumed was the best place in the world to learn, a contemporary-era Greek symposium that promoted the two pillars of civilization: free thinking and tolerance.
However, within two weeks of taking my place at Worcester College in the late 1980s to study history, I had packed my bags, which triggered the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down and cried.
My friends were puzzled.
The Evening Standard newspaper claimed that I had dropped out because I would not tolerate some college roommates having sex in the next room.
Writer A. N. Wilson jokingly announced that I had left because I was forced to drink out of chipped cups.
The truth was less fun.
I ran away from there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my fancy name, nor the fact that I came from a private school.
I was harassed for one reason only, which in the cradle of so-called enlightenment was somewhat bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent advisor to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the Conservative Party.
You may be wondering what that's all about now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of center-right students is suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred of Conservative Party students is such at Oxford that, last week, a group of them demanded the same level of equal rights that homosexuals, the disabled and ethnic minorities have.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's JCR (undergraduate student group) claim they are "often seriously ostracized, personally attacked and treated as personae non gratae" because of their political views.
They want to create a seat on their college's equal opportunity committee to ensure that they can express their opinions freely.
Their situation was not helped by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" about student politics that portrayed the Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It showed graduate student Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Party Association (OUCA), in a Rolls-Royce, sporting a silver suit and a cane with a silver grip.
At other universities, conservative students say they are being treated as "scapegoats" for the introduction of higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the Conservative Party Association at Nottingham University, told a Sunday newspaper that "there is a growing left-wing trend in universities.
People assume we are like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing us."
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history major at Corpus Christi who filed the motion for greater protection, says this environment is "uncomfortable," while Stephanie Cherill, 19, OUCA president-elect, says the attitude of JCR members toward people who are center-right has worsened.
"This poses a threat to the environment of intellectual debate as well as to the well-being of members," he says.
During my first few weeks in Oxford I was as lonely as the next person.
I entered college in September 1986, a terribly shy 18-year-old.
Hatred of the Conservative Party was at an all-time high.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an honorary degree following cuts in Higher Education funding.
The atmosphere would have made any Stalinist shudder with horror.
Already during the first days of the week of welcoming new university students, when the new students meet and get to know the professors, I received a taste of the bitterness that awaited me.
I found that professors not only turned a blind eye to the mockery of conservative academics, but participated in it willingly.
The politics of the miners' strike, privatization and the government's opposition to sanctions against apartheid in South Africa found their way into the wooden rooms of the seminary.
The first one I attended involved translating 18th century French texts into English and I was not prepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I didn't give a single one.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake batter, knew well how to expel bad bile.
"Is it that the Thatcherites refuse to learn French or is it that they are simply stupid?" he asked.
The other college students laughed.
My eyes were burning from the tears I was trying to hold back.
"I suggest she go to French lessons in her spare time, as long as she's not too busy meeting people," Pitt growled.
I went back to my room like a soul in pain.
That night I sat alone at dinnertime at the university; then I felt a light pat on my back.
He was a sophomore English major named James who introduced himself as a member of OUCA.
"I know who you are," he told me kindly.
"I'm afraid that's the way it goes.
They pick on anyone suspected of being a Tory.
For me it is very complicated, but they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so for you it will be even worse.
Many newcomer Tories pretend to be Labour."
Later, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to dissemble.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything Mrs. Thatcher said.
That trick turned out to be useless.
A first-year Philosophy, Politics and Economics student who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You are contaminated.
Other students adopted that ditty.
I became the dirty pervert.
"How do Tories have sex?" asked one.
"They beat the crap out of each other, don't they?"
I felt the same way homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 1960s.
Could I ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Would I have to become Labor and repress my natural tendencies?
The three years ahead of me looked like a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History assigned to my college.
They hated him for being not only from the Conservative party, but also Thatcher's foreign policy advisor and one of the people who wrote her speeches.
I was barely around.
He detested the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You're not going to be happy here," he told me.
I began commuting daily from Oxford to my parents' home in London, finding refuge with my more open-minded metropolitan family and friends.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he studied there in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said sadly.
"They would never do that, not there among my beloved dream needles.
Even my communist friends always had an impeccable attitude."
His sore eyes began to cloud over.
"Give him another chance.
I'm sure they just did it as a joke.
It would break my heart if you left him."
Exhausted from so many trips to London, my emotional stamina was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another history professor had implied, in all seriousness, that I was an "enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Red with shame inside, I admitted that my parents had "brainwashed" me and called them "stupid old men."
The truce was short-lived.
It was my father who put the final nail in the coffin of my college career at Oxford.
At that time my father wrote two weekly columns in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I was inside huddled in fear and, after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left I packed my suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You may call me a weak crybaby.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such a level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, which has not only trained 14 Conservative party prime ministers but, to this day, hides behind a far from deserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to notoriety."
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino: Master of Couture", which opened this week in London, ABC talks to Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous clients of the Italian designer.
Somerset House, former residence of Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition on Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this during the opening of "Valentino: Master of Couture", a spectacular retrospective that brings together more than 130 haute couture dresses created by his "maison" over the past 50 years.
"I love this palace," he says in his unmistakable Italian accent.
This exhibition is the culmination of a story whose only protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without his distinguished clients.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the rarefied and distant world of nobility.
The first room of this exhibition, open until March 3, is filled with private letters and photos signed by the highest echelons of the aristocracy, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margaret of England.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social ascent: from humble couturier in the town of Voghera, in northern Italy, to idol of the international jet-set.
There is nothing wrong with being in love with royalty.
"At least they don't put out their cigarette butts on your gorgeous carpet like some beautiful pop celebrities do," says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 1960s and 1970s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular host and entertains with generosity and elegance.
"We all loved to be invited to his chalet in Gstaad", explains the ex-wife of "Heini" Thyssen, intimate of forgotten beauties such as Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to notoriety.
And yet, he is a star.
Valeria Mazza, wearing Valentino
Argentinean model Valeria Mazza has not forgotten the couturier's charisma either.
Many years ago, after a fashion show in Piazza di Spagna in Rome, we went to dinner at his apartment.
There were twenty of us, including Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
In every detail of the apartment, the decoration, the food, the music, in everything you could see and feel his spirit.
"He made each of us guests feel important and loved," recalls the top model, who began working with him during Paris Haute Couture Week in 1995.
"It never goes out of style because his designs are works of art," he finishes.
Parade of lineage
Garavani's life is not a story of obsessions, but of well-requited loves.
He loves people with good education and better degrees, and they love him.
One of the galleries of Somerset House has been transformed into a glamorous sixty-meter long catwalk that proposes a role reversal: the visitor takes the place of the models and must parade down the catwalk to contemplate a dream "audience" wearing Valentino masterpieces, such as the dress chosen by Jackie Kennedy for her wedding to Aristotle Onassis, the costume worn by Monica Vitti in "La Notte", or a wool and fur coat that belonged to Empress Farah Diba.
Names such as Sibilla of Luxembourg, Gloria von Thurn und Taxis, Mette-Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria or Sophia of Habsburg shine in this audience of mannequins.
Naty Abascal and the couturier, in 2006
Many of these customers say that the first Valentino is like the first love, "impossible to forget".
I remember it perfectly.
It was a pair of pants, a shirt, a "gillette" vest and a jacket from the 1971-1972 autumn-winter collection.
"It was a gift he gave me," says Naty Abascal, one of the designer's muses.
"I prefer him over others for his femininity, for his great love for women, because he enhances our beauty," adds the former Duchess of Feria.
I really like the colors he uses, they have great light and are "donor" to the face.
The proportions are perfect.
Princess and fashion prescriber Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg can't forget the first time she wore a Valentino either.
When I was a teenager living in Italy, I dreamed of being old enough and having the opportunity to wear one of his evening gowns...
The time finally came in the late 1990s.
I bought my first Valentino dress to wear to a party at the chateau of my cousin, Prince Edouard de Ligne.
It was a red suit, with a ruffled skirt, draped corsage and a strapless neckline.
"It was a dream come true," says Rodrigo d'Arenberg's widow.
"Valentino is indifferent to fashion, his obsession is timeless," explains this Italian aristocrat who lives between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
Princess D'Arenberg keeps her evening dresses from the couturier with "the utmost care... because a dress is not just a dress, it is also the set of memories it brings with it".
The "king" of fashion
The grand finale of the Somerset House exhibition is Marie-Chantal Miller's wedding gown from her wedding to Paul of Greece in 1995.
It took four months of work and 25 "ragazze" (as the couturier calls his seamstresses) to create this ivory silk gown inlaid with pearls, twelve different types of lace and a tail of four and a half meters.
According to journalist Suzy Menkes, the highest authority in the specialized press, that dress represents a milestone in haute couture at the end of the 20th century, "the return of the high society clientele".
Obsessed for years with the "savoir-être" of the elite, Valentino is now its best example.
Cavaliere di Gran Croce (the highest distinction in Italy), Cavaliere del Lavoro, Commandeur de L'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres, decorated with the Legion of Honor, Garavani accumulates as many honors as any of his clients' husbands.
"I have always been struck by its refinement, its calmness, its neat and perfect appearance," D'Arenberg acknowledges.
The last time I saw him was a month ago at a gala dinner at the Musée d'Orsay.
He was at the table of Countess Jacqueline de Ribes, a great friend of mine.
"He was impeccable, time does not pass for him."
If a princess says so...
The world's toughest job: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian volcano porters risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur up steep stone trails
There are people for whom their work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to descend each day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth solidifies on contact with the air.
After pulling up large sulfur rocks, weighing a total of about 70 kilograms, he carries them in two bamboo baskets over his shoulders along steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2,386 meters, but it takes the exhausted porters more than 40 minutes to ascend at a snail's pace, keeping their balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall down the precipice.
They know that any misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the Kawah Ijen cliffs years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulfur they mine
Once at the top, they make their way through the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, wearily carrying the heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scales that a mining company has placed a little further down, at 1,850 meters above sea level.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, who are paid 662 Indonesian rupiah (5 euro cents) for each kilogram of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kilos, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) each trip," explains Anto, who usually carries three loads a day.
It takes him three hours on each one and he ends up ground down, but they allow him to collect 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems like a pittance for such inhuman effort, it is three times what I would earn in the field.
"The miners' wages are very high here, where coffee picking is paid at 15,000 rupiah (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupiah (167 euros)," says the porter, who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupiah (6.2 euros) a day and the work was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a compelling reason that, in Indonesia, is as blunt as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindu, and I have brought her to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto has asthma, has difficulty breathing, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic fumes.
At 27 years of age, Anto has been risking his life in the Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll despite the fact that he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases emitted by the volcano.
It is the price he must pay to achieve his dream.
"I will work for two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Chastened by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, a waiter or a hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing a filthy wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and glows in the dark.
Braving the shadows, Anto descends into the crater with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
Some 400 porters carry the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its handsome profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur extraction to save costs, nor does it supply any equipment to the porters, who work on their own and at their own weight.
In fact, they don't even see part of the 30,000 rupiah (2.5 euros) camera surcharge that, along with the 15,000 rupiah (1.2 euros) entrance fee, the rangers of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for beasts and not for people," protests Madrusin, a burly 42-year-old porter who has been on the Kawah Ijen for three decades, since he left school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, she says she will keep working "as long as she can" because she needs the money to raise her three children, aged 18 and 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life.
Although the sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and traps the miners in the thick columns coming out of the volcano, they are so tough that none of them complains of serious illnesses... beyond, of course, their usual respiratory problems, arthrosis, knee pains and sores on their shoulders, which have been malformed by the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at 53 years of age.
Every day, he and his colleagues remove 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks take to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away along a goat path through the undergrowth.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," proclaims Unainik, opening wide his mouth, where he is missing several teeth.
Of his five sons, the oldest, 30, also works loading sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest trades in the world: that of the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
Singapore seeks babies to save economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress and the cost of property and education for not having children.
"Singapore's population needs to grow."
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, let's fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It may seem implausible that these verses are part of an ad for mints, but despite that - or perhaps because of that - the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The phrases are part of a rap that uses local references such as "Let's put a bao (bun) in the oven" to make fun of Singapore's birth rate.
The advertising company that made the video, BBH, hopes that the ad will draw attention to the problem in a fun way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do "their national duty."
This is purely an internet thing, so we had to make it fun and funny.
It is the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world at reproducing ourselves, so we felt this was an issue we needed to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as launching pheromone perfumes or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So we thought, why don't we do the most creative thing possible to solve this problem, which is to compose a rap?
1,2 children
The one that doesn't take it so lightly is the Singapore government.
It spends US$1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leadership and its strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, according to its national population division, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 - known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Division, says it's because of "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities."
"That has allowed people to have a wider range of choices in terms of life goals and priorities beyond getting married and starting a family," he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in singleness, and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a declining birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy that aims to drastically increase immigration to cope with the declining population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, websites abound with thinly disguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, particularly the Chinese, whom they criticize for keeping wages low and not integrating.
Increased immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why last year Singapore's ruling party experienced its worst election result since independence.
Since the election there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with higher quotas and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While falling birth rates have known effects on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, healthcare costs and immigration policies, the Singapore example is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to prevent so many small houses from being built.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has moved to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoeboxes," that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a surface area of 46 square meters and have been very successful in sales.
However, there is concern that they may promote a bachelor lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large, family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, managing director of real estate firm EL Developers, says his "shoeboxes" sell much faster than larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that the units sell out days, even weeks, faster than the larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new rules give clearer guidance for developers, who were previously hindered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city state.
While these new rules may be a step toward increasing the national birth rate, talking to Singaporeans working in the downtown financial district it would seem that they are not going to have much effect.
"People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so many people are putting it off," says one young executive.
Other people may have children.
"But for me it's important to have my own money and time," says another young man in his 20s.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and the cost of property and education as the reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, as much as the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to baby-making, Singaporeans have the final say.
Private off line is private on line
Privacy.
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, it refers to the quality of privacy or "the sphere of private life that one has the right to protect from any intrusion".
What is private for a child under 16 years of age?
How do you apply this definition in your daily life and social networks?
Do you understand the dangers you are exposed to by airing situations on the Internet that you would certainly not share offline?
elPeriódico interviewed five boys between the ages of ten and 15, frequent users of the network.
In four of the cases, they associated the term with "something very much mine", on a personal level, and "in the password and user name", when applied to social networks.
"My deepest secrets I wouldn't upload to a post," says ten-year-old Jorge as he tries to explain the meaning of private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They are very secret secrets, my mom may know them, but not everyone," she says.
On FB I upload nice or game pictures.
I also entertain myself with my acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't of me, or someone making a fool of themselves," he says.
The child recognizes that it is wrong to post obscene pictures, pictures of naked people, pictures of crimes or to write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge claims to know the 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
The mother is included, she has the password to one of the accounts.
I opened Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they answer me, I just upload them," he adds.
"Social networking is fun, I can talk to distant relatives or my friends quickly," he says.
He does not hesitate to answer that he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
Nor would I listen to someone who recommended a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has open accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, in the latter he admits not knowing 20 of the people added to his friends list.
"It doesn't scare me, because we have something in common, music for example," he says.
According to the boy, none of them have approached him or asked for his home address or phone number.
"If they pressured me or demanded it I would just take them out of my account," he admits.
Jose became a follower of Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is no stranger to experiences of what is now known as cyberbullying.
An acquaintance of a friend of mine was being extorted on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who I was," she assures.
The victim, according to José, did not close the account.
"He just put privacy on it."
It then explains a series of steps to securely set up the account.
Unlike Jorge, this guy would upload photos of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would, if I don't like him or feel like it.
"Even though I know that's cyberbullying," he says.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher with a degree in Education and Learning, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents, it must be understood that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet emerged as a means to search for information, but with the emergence of these sites the rules of the game changed," he mentions.
Porras points out that the academic Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in pedagogy from Yale University and is the author of the book Digital Natives and Immigrants, coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
They are the digital natives, the children and young people who were born with technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them, when we are still learning," he says.
He comments that the issue is complex, "because we are asking them to have a defined criterion on what is or is not convenient to broadcast, publish or say at an age when maturity is not enough for that".
"Also that they are selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents what privacy is is through thought-provoking questions.
"Telling them not to do it doesn't help," he adds.
Below, Porras lists some options: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like them to post a photo of you like the one you posted of a friend?
Do you know what others post about you?
When you tag party photos, did you ask permission from the other people to tag them?
And one more, does everyone need to know what you are doing every moment?
Another point is to make them see that they must act on line as they do off line.
They are the same rules.
"One outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, it should be the same in social networks," he says.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, elementary school teacher and educational consultant, says that it is essential for parents to read social network policies thoroughly.
By understanding each of the items, they have a solid foundation for talking to their children about the implications of opening an Internet account.
"For example, age and what you are allowed to share or post," he says.
According to Guardia, it is key to remind children of the "don't talk to strangers" lesson.
Unasur Summit ends without issuing the Lima Declaration
The VI Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without making public the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven presidents attending.
Efe tried repeatedly to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially stated that it would be delivered after the closing ceremony, but later stated that it would be published at some point on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they stated that the content had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to Summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room without sound, with the message "private session, audio restricted".
The little information that circulated among reporters was provided by the press spokespersons of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian government.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents in attendance, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Subsequently, the Peruvian Presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is Humala's pronouncement, not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South America-Arab Countries Summit (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been previously announced, was not disseminated either.
On the official ASPA website it can be corroborated that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities made every effort to ensure that there were secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited as much as possible the gathering of information.
The summit also concluded with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Court of The Hague to settle a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the ICJ, which begins on Monday in The Hague to hear the arguments of both parties in the process that Lima filed against Santiago.
"We will abide by and execute the sentence that defines the differences that today we are taking to this international court," said Humala, together with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international courts," Piñera added, and greeted Humala with a handshake, together with the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Pact of Bogota by which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of that international tribunal, following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered seriously flawed.
The summit was held with the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 following the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after midday in Lima.
The President read the final document in which he informed that 16 agreements were adopted and lines of action were established for 31 projects between the South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are expanding the agreements on residency".
He informed that actions are being promoted to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, access to internet at low prices in all corners of South America, and to jointly and efficiently address the risks of natural disasters".
With Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but should serve to expand our productive matrix and glimpse a better future for our peoples," added Humala.
"We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas...uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," the Peruvian president said in a message read.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two are aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for its reincorporation into the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations between neighbors, was another of the issues highlighted by the summit.
In this regard, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before beginning his participation in the regional meeting that he expected to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to respectfully discuss the maritime dispute following an ICJ ruling, questioned by Bogota.
"Tomorrow (Saturday) it is possible that I will have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We are going to review all these paths, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua," he stressed.
"With President Ortega I hope to be able to tell him that we handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega are scheduled to meet on Saturday in Mexico where they plan to attend the inauguration of the new Mexican president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Likewise, as part of the summit, the defense ministers of the bloc met previously to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defense matters in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn from Europe to integrate citizenship": Rafael Correa
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, affirmed today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal in which "South America, in this case yes, must learn from Europe".
Correa, who participated in the VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), held in Lima, told state-owned TV Peru that Europeans "killed each other in World War II" and in other conflicts, "but now they are practically a homeland".
In this sense, he defended the project to establish South American citizenship encouraged by the member countries of Unasur.
"We must achieve free mobility of citizens and workers in any South American country, as is already happening with the members of the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary sectors that want to return us to the past," he warned.
The Ecuadorian president was also in favor of the recomposition of the Organization of American States (OAS) under the premise of reducing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states and taking into account those that have signed the San Jose pact on human rights.
Those who give lectures never commit themselves to anything, but we South Americans sign everything.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is in Washington under U.S. funding," he said, alluding to the political asylum given by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa assured that he does not regret this decision because he has not betrayed his principles, but has respected his "profound democratic and human rights values".
He added that, at the time, "there were well-founded suspicions that Assange would be extradited to a third country and his process would not be respected."
He also criticized the Swedish justice system for demanding that he submit himself in its territory to interrogation for an alleged sex crime when "Swedish law itself allows this to be done by videoconference, which could be done from the Ecuadorian embassy in London".
Correa stated that there is a risk that Assange's physical and mental health could deteriorate.
"I have not spoken to him since he has been in our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he had a small lung problem, nothing serious," said the Ecuadorian president.
What there is is the danger of deteriorating their physical and mental health by being confined in a small space without being able to exercise outdoors.
"That complicates anyone's health," he added.
Correa pointed out that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, through the granting of a safe-conduct allowing him to travel to Ecuador, is in the hands of Great Britain, Sweden and the European legal authorities and stressed that there have been talks with London in search of a solution to the confinement of the WikiLeaks founder.
We do not negotiate with human rights, we do not use that word in this case, but there have been permanent conversations.
"The solution to this problem is in the hands of Great Britain, Sweden and the European legal authorities because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, is making a series of procedures in different European instances," he mentioned.
And he opined that "if Great Britain gives tomorrow the safe conduct this is over".
And if Sweden, as its legislation perfectly allows and as it has done in other cases, interrogates Mr. Assange in the Ecuadorian embassy in London or interrogates him via Skype tomorrow, this problem will be over.
Correa took the opportunity to reaffirm his position as a defender of freedom of the press and added that what he does not tolerate is "mediocrity, bad faith and lies, which distort freedom of expression".
"The greatest enemies of press freedom are not evil and perverse politicians but bad journalists for profit, blackmail and extortion," he said.
In this regard, he was pleased that these journalists "neither the bankers nor the hegemonic and bourgeois countries are no longer the ones who dominate Ecuador", and said that if re-elected "he will deepen the revolution to continue on the right path and in the right direction".
Correa also supported the decision to maintain Paraguay's veto in Unasur at least until its next elections, arguing that the organization "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and coups dressed up as legality" because in reality "it destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
The Ecuadorian president also considered "perfectly pertinent" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate now with Nicaragua the maritime limits between both countries after the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which benefited Nicaraguan maritime sovereignty.
For the time being, this ruling is not being complied with.
It is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to walk together.
It is necessary to process them in a comprehensive manner in order to overcome them and move forward.
He also hoped for a good conclusion to the maritime boundary dispute between Peru and Chile in the same court and said that "it is right for Latin America to seek international instances if both countries are committed to accept a ruling, no matter how harsh it may be".
In reference to the possibility that he may run as a candidate in the next presidential elections in Ecuador to seek a third consecutive term, he said that he views this possibility "with much optimism and joy, although sometimes it is quite hard".
Correa assured that if he loses the February 2013 elections he will retire from public life.
Personally, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unjust as Ecuador's, such socioeconomic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed that probable victory, so we have to accept that responsibility," he said.
If I win, it would be my last term in the presidency and from there we leave public life.
If we lose the same.
"It's a decision," he said.
Correa also referred to the new health treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolas Maduro and he tells me that he traveled for a treatment that was already planned, routine, that he waited for the campaign to pass before returning to Cuba.
"It does not mean a relapse in President Chavez's health condition", he commented.
The Ecuadorian head of state participated today in Lima in the VI Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which concluded with calls for greater regional integration to sustain progress, equality and security.
Deaths from AIDS today are due to late detection
Fabrizio was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: AIDS positive.
"It was like a bomb dropped on me," he says, recalling the moment of the announcement, which the doctor tried to make "softer," without obvious success.
The boy hid it from his family.
He decided to take charge of his illness on his own and began to learn more about it, so much so that he has already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV Unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), where he arrived in 1994 after several battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he had a cut".
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and to do so with quality of life.
However, unaware of their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already wreaked havoc, "exhausted" their immune system and become victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, at least of the first reported cases, "the great achievement at this moment means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population is exactly the same", indicated the head of the HCG HIV Unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, after referring that this information was endorsed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
An infectologist and expert in HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists had concluded that AIDS was not a fatal sentence, but the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of affectation of the immune system that patients present at the beginning of the diagnosis, with better expectations for those who are not drug users: up to 30 years with a CD4 count of 200 and 50 years, when they report 500 CD4.
In simple words, this means that those who are diagnosed HIV positive at 25 years of age, under these terms "as long as they remain under control, they will be able to live without problems until they are 75 years old", explained the interviewee.
To measure this progress, it is worth remembering that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
While mortality has dropped significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS dropped from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the emergence of AIDS, 60 percent of patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there have been 187 deaths up to May of this year; however, it is assured that there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still deaths?
- It seems to me that the problem is not one of access to treatment.
That's how I visualize it, that's how it has happened to us in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years we have had no shortage of medication, the problem is that patients arrive very advanced because they are unaware of their infection status, that is, in late stages of the disease.
He gave a convincing fact: "Nine out of every ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection. What needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, therefore, screening tests must be offered on a massive scale to all those who require them".
Specialists and officials of the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco (Coesida) agree with his proposal, as do the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who went to a private laboratory for the test, motivated only because a friend had done it and, despite his young age, he was already in the AIDS stage and even suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they are going to die and don't want to know anything.
"If I'm already going to die, I might as well bust three times a week," they say, not in my case.
The change was for the better, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medications.
To date, his parents only know that he suffered from cancer.
I live a normal life, like anyone else.
"I work, I have many activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I take care of myself and the other person," listed Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to motivate with his testimony those who today, in the framework of World AIDS Day, are afraid.
If they were at risk, the sooner they know if they are HIV positive, the better, and if they are already diagnosed, they should learn that they can live like any other person, being responsible.
That, his message, sums up the slogan of the battle against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are large gaps between health programs and the common citizen, said Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken up the cause of HIV.
And the biggest is in prevention.
In the places dedicated to this task "the distribution of condoms has effectively increased, before they gave us one or two, now they give us packs of one hundred, and that is very good, but it turns out that there are those who still do not have access to a condom," he said.
Among those most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
"What do you want them for?" is a common question, with derision and value judgments from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy employees and health personnel, to which adolescents do not want to be exposed, said the communicator.
He proposed to reorient this inefficient distribution; that condoms should not be only behind the counters and that these 100 condoms should be found in public restroom dispensers in places frequented by young people.
It is not to encourage promiscuity.
Nor is it a matter of paying for their drinks and motel, as Governor Emilio Gonzalez answered when asked if condoms would be distributed in his administration.
"That's not how sexuality is, the best thing to do is to bring condoms closer to those who are already sexually active," he said.
Keys In Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state is 4th nationally in new and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th in HIV.
