With the ratification by a U.S. appeals court of a ruling that disregards the restructuring of Grupo Vitro's debt achieved through a bankruptcy proceeding in Mexico, the scenario sets an ominous precedent for any national company with branches in the neighboring country that has solvency problems.
It would seem, therefore, that the procedures in support of the survival of the firms allowed by Mexican law are not valid in the country of the stars and stripes, contrary to international conventions.
On a practical level, the endorsement of the ruling issued on June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican firms defenseless against the possibility of seizure of their properties across the Rio Grande.
However, the ruling opens the door for Mexico's leading glass manufacturer to go to the U.S. Supreme Court, alleging three inconsistencies.
First of all, while the judge in the case states that the creditors must abide by the U.S. Bankruptcy Law, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, says that the main proceeding is the insolvency proceeding in Mexico.
The first point would imply disregarding international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, to this end, the United Nations Model Law for Uniformity in International Trade Law was created, with the American Law Institute acting as arbitrator.
Second, the judgment establishes that without the intercompany vote, the debts owed to the parent company by Vitro's subsidiaries being recognized in the critical mass of the insolvency proceeding, the majority required to approve the restructuring would not have been achieved.
However, the possibility is recognized by Mexican law.
In fact, Vitro's was not the first case in which the scheme was accepted.
There are half a dozen examples, among them Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose intercompany debts were endorsed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy (Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles).
Furthermore, subtracting the votes of the subsidiaries, Vitro's creditors that fought against Vitro in the U.S. Courts, i.e. the "vulture" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot International and Liverpool Limited, will not have obtained a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent to 37.
This fact is omitted by the Court of Appeals.
From another angle, he blames Vitro for the difficult situation it faced from 2008 onwards in the wake of the severe economic crisis faced by the United States, which hit the country hard.
For the time being, the González Sada family firm will file an appeal for reconsideration before the appeals court itself so that the vote may reach the full court, that is to say the five judges, since only three voted.
If this does not succeed, the Cerciorare remedy will be claimed, which requires the review of the process by a higher instance, in this case the Supreme Court of Justice of the United States.
The seriousness of the case is that the court overlooked a document sent by the Mexican government as amicus curiae ("friend of the Court"), which details the procedure followed by Vitro under the framework of the Bankruptcy Law, indicating that it was carried out in accordance with the agreements signed by both countries to match it with Chapter 15 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Law.
Furthermore, it is noted that the country has adhered to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules established for cross-border insolvency cases, which guarantee fairness for debtors and creditors.
Two-sided carambola: they hit Vitro and they hit the country.
