Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball has been my life".
Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has been linked to basketball for more than 60 years and, thanks to him, he has traveled the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a mental recollection of the history of local basketball as broad as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has.
Before a stroke confined him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a youth player, a National Superior Basketball player, an agent and leader in the BSN with the Bayamón Vaqueros or president of the Basketball Federation.
"I wore many hats in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time, such as when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the National Team and federation president during the 1990s," recalled Reyes during a Primera Hora visit to his home in Bayamón, where he resides with Isabel, his faithful wife of more than 50 years.
"Basketball has been my life."
Reyes is not exaggerating in making this assertion.
The walls of his home, almost all decorated with photos and memorabilia denoting his extensive career, attest to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all of them, the ones he treasures with the greatest emotion are those that recall his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s as a player until 1982, when he served 15 years as co-captain or manager of the franchise.
"Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most because I had the opportunity to be part of eight championships for the Vaqueros since 1967, whether as a proxy, co-prospect or manager.
There were many satisfying years, including the five championships run from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye with one in 1981, Jerome Mincy's debut year in the BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took over," said Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had coached here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me, "I've got a very strong player for you, 6'7" tall.
Do you want it?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended sniper Raymond Gausse, who was nativized and was one of our best marksmen.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had given Bayamon a championship, Gausse would help bring one more.
He enjoyed the championship of the Vaqueros with Gausse, but already at a distance, because by 1988 he was already the head of the federation.
By that time he preferred to enjoy his and Mincy's performances on the National Team.
I remember when we beat the United States for the first time during the Pre-Olympic in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we came in fourth place and should have been bronze had it not been for that Canadian referee who made us replay the final play a second time, Reyes said.
Is that 1990 World Cup group the best National Team you have ever seen?
It is among the best, just like the one that beat the Dream Team in the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and beat the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that won us the bronze medal at the World Cup.
That team not only had Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but also (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter as youngsters, the León brothers (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to play in the 90's due to a knee injury.
A team that perhaps was not the best in terms of personnel, but gave us a gold medal and a great joy was the 1995 Pre-Olympic in Neuquén, Argentina.
With role players such as "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and a youthful Rolando Hourruitiner replacing the players suspended due to the Mar del Plata Pan American Games, we won gold against all odds.
Who has been the best player in Puerto Rico?
Undoubtedly, that has been Piculín Ortiz.
His numbers at the international tournament level are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at that level as Piculín did.
And that's not counting his career in the different leagues he played in.
Who has been the best Puerto Rican leader?
That one is very difficult.
We have had a very good crop that includes Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
Of the young people, I really like the work of Leo Arill.
What do you consider your greatest achievement in the federation?
Having been part of the most glorious era of the National Team between 1988 and 1995 and that in the early 90's the BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What did you have left to do?
There were things I would have liked to implement, such as the regionalization of the lower categories.
For example, the Ponce boys will only play in their area and will only face teams from other corners of the island in the national playoffs.
Right now children travel and play too much unnecessarily.
At least I see the fruits of the compulsory certifications and courses for officials, table officials and referees.
That pleases me.
What are you doing now?
The most I do is listen to music, watch music videos from my era on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to basketball games.
And of course, enjoying the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Actor Larry Hagman dies
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became world famous for his central role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.," in the television series "Dallas," in which he played an unscrupulous, malicious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the TV series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday afternoon due to complications from cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by "Dallas" producer Warner Bros.
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again portraying the iconic role he loved the most," the family said.
Larry's family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said her publicist, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to everyone he met.
He was creative, generous, fun, funny, caring and talented, and I will miss him dearly.
"He was an original person and lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and acknowledged that he had been drinking heavily for years.
In 1995 he was found to have a malignant tumor in his liver and underwent a transplant.
Years before "Dallas," Hagman made a name for himself on television as a decent guy on the light comedy "I Dream of Jeannie," broadcast on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life is altered when he meets an attractive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and takes her home to live with him.
He also starred in two short-lived sitcoms, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included critically well-received roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful portrayal of the charmingly obnoxious J.R. that brought Hagman to the height of his stardom.
The CBS network drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in their orbit aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional phrase "Who shot J.R.?", designed to generate expectation around an emotionally charged episode in which Hagman's character is almost killed, generated international speculation and millions of dollars risked at bookmakers.
It also helped give the series record ratings at the time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers tuned in, making "Dallas" the second most-watched entertainment program in history, behind the 1983 finale of "MASH," which had 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. impregnated her and then threatened to brand her a prostitute unless she left town, but others also had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing as an insatiable crook with a charismatic smile: a cheating businessman and a cheating husband who tried to have his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), committed.
"I know what I want on J.R.'s tombstone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should read, "Here lies honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only business he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, remembered Hagman on Friday as someone "huge, on and off the screen."
He is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us who were lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were aired a few months ago with great success on TNT channel.
Filming had already finished on five of the episodes for the second season and a sixth was in process, the network reported.
There was no immediate statement from Warner or TNT on how the series will handle the loss of Hagman.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who starred in such classics as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Martin was still a teenager when she had him in 1931 during her marriage to attorney Ben Hagman.
He tried his luck on the New York theatrical stage in the early 1950s, and then served in the Air Force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
While there he met the young Swedish designer Maj Axelsson and married her.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for a long time in the California city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001 he titled his memoir "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life".
"I didn't put anything in there that I thought was going to hurt anyone or affect them in any way," he told the Associated Press at the time.
After the liver transplant he became an advocate for organ donation and volunteered at a hospital to assist fearful patients.
"I counsel them, I give them courage, I meet with them when they come in for their surgeries, and afterwards," he said in 1996.
I try to offer some comfort, such as "don't be afraid, it will be a little uncomfortable for a short time, but you're going to be fine."
He was also an activist against smoking and participated in several campaigns.
Course to explore the "End of the World" begins
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible hook: the end of the Mayan Calendar's "long countdown" on December 21, which many people have clung to as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what the next couple of months had in store for him: the cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal cliff that some have called "deudarmageddon," and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian end-times theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers University-Camden (N.J.) this week.
If you look at what has been happening in the world today as if we were 30 days and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember that bad is good for those with an apocalyptic mentality.
And he is not the only professor offering courses on the "end of the world" this semester, theoretically the last in history.
At Temple, Associate Professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze why these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and how they provide hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, war could break out.
This month students analyzed movies with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
"I have tried to inform students about what is possible, probable, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled only "The End of the World."
"We didn't add '2012' so that we always have the option to teach the course again, in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the "imminent ruin", students must study, generate projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "right up until the very night the world is supposed to end," Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
"It overcrowded in two hours," Restall said of his course for high GPA students, which filled up with 35 students.
We received email messages for weeks and weeks before the start of the semester from people asking if there was still room.
The students, for their part, say that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves," said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old Religion and Sociology major from Haddonfield, N.J., at Rutgers-Camden.
The apocalyptic mentality, secular or religious, is only a matter of consolation or the absence of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old Psychology and Nursing major, said he has seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I'd never heard of a class that could teach that," he noted.
I enjoy it.
But no student interviewed - let alone a teacher - said they believed in the Dec. 21 expiration date.
"Our first project was about the Mayan prophecy and we kind of debunked it," said Temple senior Julie Zeglen, 21, of West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it is just a key point on the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, going back several centuries, in which people react to changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a boom in such speculation.
"Elsewhere people don't think about this," he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University teaching courses in the Philippines this year, was quick to respond to a question about whether he knew of any "end of the world" courses there.
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world," he wrote, hinting at an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many doomsdays, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they plan to go to "end of the world" parties.
"Maybe I'll call some friends so we can laugh together," commented Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
